00:00:27.100 --> 00:00:29.380
PROFESSOR: Welcome to Teaching
College-Level Science and

00:00:29.380 --> 00:00:31.340
engineering.

00:00:31.340 --> 00:00:35.530
The title contains the word
teaching, which may spark some

00:00:35.530 --> 00:00:36.460
questions in your mind.

00:00:36.460 --> 00:00:40.270
For example, is teaching
just an art?

00:00:40.270 --> 00:00:44.240
Or is it something that's just
something you're born with?

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:47.970
In which case, either you have
it or you don't have it.

00:00:47.970 --> 00:00:50.630
Well, obviously, I don't believe
that, or I wouldn't be

00:00:50.630 --> 00:00:51.820
teaching a course on it.

00:00:51.820 --> 00:00:53.210
What would be the point?

00:00:53.210 --> 00:00:56.770
Or is it purely a science
where there's a set of

00:00:56.770 --> 00:00:59.790
equations and procedures to
learn, and then all of a

00:00:59.790 --> 00:01:02.260
sudden, you'll be an
excellent teacher?

00:01:02.260 --> 00:01:04.599
Well, actually, it's neither.

00:01:04.599 --> 00:01:05.670
And it's both.

00:01:05.670 --> 00:01:09.910
It's things that we're all born
with, on the one hand.

00:01:09.910 --> 00:01:13.290
And there're also procedures
and techniques and ways of

00:01:13.290 --> 00:01:16.020
thinking that will improve
how you teach and

00:01:16.020 --> 00:01:17.260
that we can all learn.

00:01:17.260 --> 00:01:20.540
So it's a happy mix,
my favorite mix,

00:01:20.540 --> 00:01:23.140
an art and a science.

00:01:23.140 --> 00:01:26.160
So another example that's
an art and the

00:01:26.160 --> 00:01:29.500
science is book design.

00:01:29.500 --> 00:01:33.110
So compared to, for example,
just pure art--

00:01:33.110 --> 00:01:34.940
painting, say modern
painting--

00:01:34.940 --> 00:01:39.770
very unconstrained, versus say
biology procedures in the

00:01:39.770 --> 00:01:44.930
laboratory, very, very
closely specified.

00:01:44.930 --> 00:01:46.410
It's somewhere in between.

00:01:46.410 --> 00:01:48.900
There's an art--

00:01:48.900 --> 00:01:52.740
all the arts of color, space--

00:01:52.740 --> 00:01:56.310
but they all have to be used
together to achieve a

00:01:56.310 --> 00:01:57.740
particular purpose.

00:01:57.740 --> 00:02:00.800
So again, in there, there's
some beautifully designed

00:02:00.800 --> 00:02:03.270
books and some not so
beautifully designed books.

00:02:03.270 --> 00:02:06.740
And there're principles behind
that that we can use to design

00:02:06.740 --> 00:02:07.250
good books.

00:02:07.250 --> 00:02:10.060
And similarly, there are
principles we can use to

00:02:10.060 --> 00:02:11.840
design good teaching.

00:02:11.840 --> 00:02:14.600
So the whole point of this
semester is to design good

00:02:14.600 --> 00:02:16.350
teaching and how you do that.

00:02:16.350 --> 00:02:20.000
And rather than me give you a
big long theory about it,

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:23.570
because actually there isn't
really theory so much in the

00:02:23.570 --> 00:02:26.960
equivalent to, say, Einstein's
theory of relativity.

00:02:26.960 --> 00:02:29.120
But there's principles
to learn.

00:02:29.120 --> 00:02:33.620
The best way to learn those
principles is with an example.

00:02:33.620 --> 00:02:37.930
So what we're going to do today
is I'm going to do an

00:02:37.930 --> 00:02:40.750
example of teaching with you.

00:02:40.750 --> 00:02:43.850
We're going to do a sort of
maybe slightly sped-up version

00:02:43.850 --> 00:02:47.420
of what we would normally do,
say, if we were actually using

00:02:47.420 --> 00:02:49.050
this example in a class.

00:02:49.050 --> 00:02:51.770
Then we're going to analyze
why it was done that way.

00:02:51.770 --> 00:02:54.990
And from that analysis, general
principles of teaching

00:02:54.990 --> 00:02:57.390
will come out that
will be addressed

00:02:57.390 --> 00:02:58.670
throughout the semester.

00:02:58.670 --> 00:03:01.530
And they'll be addressed
in the context

00:03:01.530 --> 00:03:03.050
of particular tasks.

00:03:03.050 --> 00:03:07.180
Like for example, how to make
slides that are useful for

00:03:07.180 --> 00:03:10.920
teaching, how to use a
blackboard, how to teach

00:03:10.920 --> 00:03:13.660
equations, how to
design a whole

00:03:13.660 --> 00:03:15.830
course, how to make problems.

00:03:15.830 --> 00:03:19.960
So all of those tasks will be
the week by week subjects.

00:03:19.960 --> 00:03:22.720
And in each task, all of the
principles that we're going to

00:03:22.720 --> 00:03:26.670
talk about now will show
up in those tasks.

00:03:26.670 --> 00:03:30.060
And you'll see the principles
illustrated repeatedly.

00:03:30.060 --> 00:03:34.290
OK, so the problem--

00:03:34.290 --> 00:03:36.420
one of my favorites.

00:03:36.420 --> 00:03:39.300
So these are two cones.

00:03:39.300 --> 00:03:42.560
One has twice the dimensions
of the other cone.

00:03:42.560 --> 00:03:44.310
So let me show you how
I made the cones.

00:03:50.460 --> 00:03:55.960
So I printed out a circle and
just cut out one quarter of

00:03:55.960 --> 00:03:58.240
the circle.

00:03:58.240 --> 00:04:00.846
And then I taped this
edge to that edge.

00:04:05.410 --> 00:04:10.520
Or in mathematician speak, I
identified the edges, which

00:04:10.520 --> 00:04:13.220
now I know means I taped
the edges together.

00:04:13.220 --> 00:04:16.200
And then you get a
cone, like that.

00:04:16.200 --> 00:04:19.850
So this cone and the other cone
were cut out of the same

00:04:19.850 --> 00:04:22.440
sheet of paper except this
one has twice the linear

00:04:22.440 --> 00:04:24.280
dimensions in its circle.

00:04:24.280 --> 00:04:28.990
So I think this circle was 7
centimeters in radius, and

00:04:28.990 --> 00:04:32.820
this is 3 and 1/2 centimeters
in radius.

00:04:32.820 --> 00:04:35.280
So other than that,
they're the same.

00:04:35.280 --> 00:04:38.870
And the question is,
which one has the

00:04:38.870 --> 00:04:40.230
higher terminal velocity?

00:04:40.230 --> 00:04:41.860
Or are they about comparable?

00:04:41.860 --> 00:04:44.640
So in particular, the
question is this.

00:04:44.640 --> 00:04:45.960
So I'm going to drop them.

00:04:45.960 --> 00:04:48.980
And the question is, what's
their ratio of their terminal

00:04:48.980 --> 00:04:50.230
velocities?

00:05:01.710 --> 00:05:05.110
So the ratio of the big cone's
terminal velocity to the small

00:05:05.110 --> 00:05:07.430
cone's terminal velocity
is equal to what.

00:05:07.430 --> 00:05:13.095
And you get choices
along this axis.

00:05:13.095 --> 00:05:14.419
So here is--

00:05:37.900 --> 00:05:40.450
OK, so those are the five
regions to choose from.

00:05:46.350 --> 00:05:48.070
So you have five choices
for the ratio,

00:05:48.070 --> 00:05:49.780
basically roughly 1/4.

00:05:49.780 --> 00:05:53.415
This is some range here, because
nothing's exact.

00:05:53.415 --> 00:05:56.880
And we're certainly not going
to do an exact experiment.

00:05:56.880 --> 00:06:01.890
Roughly 1/2, roughly 1, roughly
2, or roughly 4.

00:06:01.890 --> 00:06:04.100
So does everyone understand
the question?

00:06:04.100 --> 00:06:05.920
Because you're going to get
to try it yourself.

00:06:08.500 --> 00:06:10.072
Question about the question?

00:06:10.072 --> 00:06:11.758
AUDIENCE: If you could restate
it-- actually, there was a

00:06:11.758 --> 00:06:12.964
sign-up sheet going around
which distracted me.

00:06:12.964 --> 00:06:15.940
So I sort of lost the--

00:06:15.940 --> 00:06:17.840
PROFESSOR: Sure.

00:06:17.840 --> 00:06:18.840
Could I restate the question?

00:06:18.840 --> 00:06:20.390
No problem.

00:06:20.390 --> 00:06:23.480
So I'm going to drop them,
just like this.

00:06:23.480 --> 00:06:24.050
No tricks--

00:06:24.050 --> 00:06:27.280
I'm not going to flip this
one around or anything.

00:06:27.280 --> 00:06:29.710
And the question is,
what's the ratio of

00:06:29.710 --> 00:06:30.910
their terminal speed?

00:06:30.910 --> 00:06:34.770
So right away, as soon as you
let go of them, they come to a

00:06:34.770 --> 00:06:37.390
steady speed, which is their
terminal velocity.

00:06:37.390 --> 00:06:40.470
And the question is, how do the
terminal speeds of the big

00:06:40.470 --> 00:06:42.700
one and the small one differ?

00:06:42.700 --> 00:06:46.090
OK, so in particular, the
question is, what's the ratio?

00:06:46.090 --> 00:06:49.482
And there's five choices
for them.

00:06:49.482 --> 00:06:51.384
Does that help?

00:06:51.384 --> 00:06:51.866
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:06:51.866 --> 00:06:54.280
So what were the dimension
of them again?

00:06:54.280 --> 00:06:56.440
PROFESSOR: So this guy is--

00:06:56.440 --> 00:07:00.230
he was cut out of a circle who
was 7 centimeters in radius.

00:07:00.230 --> 00:07:02.710
And this guy was cut out of
a circle who was 3 and 1/2

00:07:02.710 --> 00:07:05.640
centimeters in radius.

00:07:05.640 --> 00:07:08.530
And then I was also very
careful to use--

00:07:08.530 --> 00:07:08.983
let's see.

00:07:08.983 --> 00:07:09.550
Did I do this right?

00:07:09.550 --> 00:07:14.510
Yeah, I used to half the with of
tape on the small guy as I

00:07:14.510 --> 00:07:18.950
did on the big guy, just to get
it really very perfectly

00:07:18.950 --> 00:07:20.650
scale invariant.

00:07:20.650 --> 00:07:22.430
OK any questions about
the question?

00:07:27.170 --> 00:07:31.220
OK, so think to yourself for
about 30 seconds or so, just

00:07:31.220 --> 00:07:34.340
to induct yourself
into the problem.

00:07:34.340 --> 00:07:36.430
And then we'll take a vote.

00:07:36.430 --> 00:07:38.870
And then you'll have a chance to
discuss it with each other.

00:08:18.840 --> 00:08:20.410
OK, let's just take a vote.

00:08:20.410 --> 00:08:24.790
So I recognize I haven't given
you at all enough time to come

00:08:24.790 --> 00:08:27.120
up with an exact answer or
calculate everything.

00:08:27.120 --> 00:08:28.980
And that's by design.

00:08:28.980 --> 00:08:31.400
So let's just get
a straw poll.

00:08:31.400 --> 00:08:33.059
And then you'll have a chance
to argue with your

00:08:33.059 --> 00:08:34.070
neighbor about it.

00:08:34.070 --> 00:08:37.900
So who votes for 1/4,
which is that the--

00:08:37.900 --> 00:08:38.320
so let's see--

00:08:38.320 --> 00:08:42.090
1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6.

00:08:42.090 --> 00:08:44.130
OK, 6.

00:08:44.130 --> 00:08:47.234
Who votes for 1/2?

00:08:47.234 --> 00:08:50.314
1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7--

00:08:53.050 --> 00:08:53.950
12.

00:08:53.950 --> 00:08:55.200
Who votes for C?

00:08:58.800 --> 00:09:00.750
22.

00:09:00.750 --> 00:09:03.860
Who votes for D?

00:09:03.860 --> 00:09:04.930
No takers.

00:09:04.930 --> 00:09:07.660
No takers for D. OK,
how about E?

00:09:11.060 --> 00:09:11.710
OK.

00:09:11.710 --> 00:09:16.830
So now find a neighbor or two,
one or two neighbors.

00:09:16.830 --> 00:09:18.290
Introduce yourself
to your neighbor.

00:09:18.290 --> 00:09:20.900
And also, by the way, unless
you're taking notes on your

00:09:20.900 --> 00:09:22.980
laptop and really insist on
doing that, if you could close

00:09:22.980 --> 00:09:25.840
your laptop, that would be very
helpful for the purpose

00:09:25.840 --> 00:09:28.890
of discussion in this
whole course.

00:09:28.890 --> 00:09:30.800
So find a neighbor or two.

00:09:30.800 --> 00:09:32.290
Introduce yourself.

00:09:32.290 --> 00:09:34.490
You'll be getting a chance to
meet graduate students from

00:09:34.490 --> 00:09:35.520
across the institute.

00:09:35.520 --> 00:09:37.420
This is a great opportunity.

00:09:37.420 --> 00:09:39.790
And try to convince them of your
answer, especially if you

00:09:39.790 --> 00:09:40.740
have a different answer.

00:09:40.740 --> 00:09:43.450
Or if you happen to share an
answer, well, see if you can

00:09:43.450 --> 00:09:44.960
figure out why you're
sure of it.

00:09:44.960 --> 00:09:47.770
Or if you're not sure of it,
see if you can settle that.

00:09:47.770 --> 00:09:51.010
OK, so discussion time.

00:09:51.010 --> 00:09:53.630
And if you have any questions
that come up as you're

00:09:53.630 --> 00:09:54.860
discussing, raise your hand.

00:09:54.860 --> 00:09:56.110
And I'll come and wander over.

00:09:59.250 --> 00:10:02.850
Meanwhile I also handed out
feedback sheets for the end of

00:10:02.850 --> 00:10:05.920
the session, which I'll ask you
to just spend a minute on

00:10:05.920 --> 00:10:06.380
at the end.

00:10:06.380 --> 00:10:10.020
But you'll notice one of the
questions is, what's the most

00:10:10.020 --> 00:10:11.240
confusing thing?

00:10:11.240 --> 00:10:13.690
So if anything really confusing
comes up during the

00:10:13.690 --> 00:10:15.480
whole session, you can just
put it right then.

00:10:15.480 --> 00:10:16.860
You don't have to wait
till the end.

00:10:16.860 --> 00:10:18.880
Or if there's something you
really liked or hated--

00:10:18.880 --> 00:10:21.680
that's question two-- you can
put that whenever it happens

00:10:21.680 --> 00:10:23.170
to come up.

00:10:23.170 --> 00:10:26.700
But vote number two, and then
we'll take some reasons.

00:10:26.700 --> 00:10:29.530
So 1/4?

00:10:32.160 --> 00:10:36.220
1, 2, 3.

00:10:36.220 --> 00:10:39.060
OK, 4.

00:10:39.060 --> 00:10:41.496
1/2--

00:10:41.496 --> 00:10:43.020
the halves don't have it.

00:10:43.020 --> 00:10:44.140
Oh, no, there's 1.

00:10:44.140 --> 00:10:44.710
Oh, there's 2.

00:10:44.710 --> 00:10:45.360
OK great--

00:10:45.360 --> 00:10:49.140
3, 4, 5, 6.

00:10:49.140 --> 00:10:50.880
Equal?

00:10:50.880 --> 00:10:54.250
OK, so that's about--
let's call it 30.

00:10:54.250 --> 00:10:55.500
2?

00:10:57.880 --> 00:11:00.670
And 4.

00:11:00.670 --> 00:11:04.280
OK so thanks for the votes.

00:11:04.280 --> 00:11:06.620
Let's take reasons
for any of them.

00:11:06.620 --> 00:11:07.715
I'll take reasons for
any of them, and

00:11:07.715 --> 00:11:09.690
I'll put them up here.

00:11:09.690 --> 00:11:11.090
You don't even have to agree
with the reason.

00:11:11.090 --> 00:11:13.800
It's just something you guys
discussed and thought maybe

00:11:13.800 --> 00:11:14.825
was plausible.

00:11:14.825 --> 00:11:16.220
AUDIENCE: C seems to
have [INAUDIBLE].

00:11:21.132 --> 00:11:23.430
When you do this kind of
activities, there is always

00:11:23.430 --> 00:11:24.955
some guys who have
seen it before.

00:11:24.955 --> 00:11:26.370
And he may choose to spoil it.

00:11:26.370 --> 00:11:28.803
So I may want to know
what you would do in

00:11:28.803 --> 00:11:29.820
that kind of situation.

00:11:29.820 --> 00:11:30.965
PROFESSOR: So you're--

00:11:30.965 --> 00:11:32.215
hm.

00:11:33.830 --> 00:11:35.080
I'm not sure how
to phrase this.

00:11:38.130 --> 00:11:41.470
Let me just take
other comments.

00:11:41.470 --> 00:11:43.560
I'll come to it afterwards.

00:11:43.560 --> 00:11:46.370
Other comments for any
of the reasons?

00:11:46.370 --> 00:11:47.960
So again, it doesn't have to
be things you necessarily

00:11:47.960 --> 00:11:50.310
believe, but things that
are plausible.

00:11:50.310 --> 00:11:53.240
And that's actually more
instructive than what you

00:11:53.240 --> 00:11:54.530
think is for sure right.

00:11:54.530 --> 00:11:57.060
Because now you're trying to
figure out what might be true.

00:11:57.060 --> 00:11:58.830
And you're expanding the
ways you're thinking.

00:11:58.830 --> 00:11:59.670
Yeah?

00:11:59.670 --> 00:12:02.900
AUDIENCE: C, because they
have identical mass to

00:12:02.900 --> 00:12:04.830
surface area ratio.

00:12:04.830 --> 00:12:05.170
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:12:05.170 --> 00:12:09.490
C, so mass to area ratio
is the same.

00:12:13.930 --> 00:12:16.160
OK, can people think of
plausible reasons

00:12:16.160 --> 00:12:17.410
against that argument?

00:12:20.860 --> 00:12:21.260
Yes.

00:12:21.260 --> 00:12:23.602
AUDIENCE: So I have no idea what
the actual formula is for

00:12:23.602 --> 00:12:24.416
calculating it.

00:12:24.416 --> 00:12:27.233
If there was a square in
there, then that would

00:12:27.233 --> 00:12:29.540
[INAUDIBLE].

00:12:29.540 --> 00:12:29.840
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:12:29.840 --> 00:12:34.420
So I'll call this Not C. So
suppose the formula actually

00:12:34.420 --> 00:12:37.270
depended on the square root
of A or square of A or

00:12:37.270 --> 00:12:39.740
something like that.

00:12:39.740 --> 00:12:42.600
It's, say, one chance out of
three that it has A to the

00:12:42.600 --> 00:12:43.830
first power here.

00:12:43.830 --> 00:12:47.460
It could have A to the
1/2 or A to the 2.

00:12:47.460 --> 00:13:00.820
So could be m over A to the
k for k not equal to 1.

00:13:03.580 --> 00:13:09.310
Others for or against C,
intuitive reasons, or for any

00:13:09.310 --> 00:13:10.560
of the others?

00:13:18.070 --> 00:13:19.640
So hopefully that's--

00:13:19.640 --> 00:13:20.360
oh, yes.

00:13:20.360 --> 00:13:20.580
Go ahead.

00:13:20.580 --> 00:13:21.830
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:13:24.680 --> 00:13:26.998
The air resistance scales
with the area.

00:13:26.998 --> 00:13:29.428
And the gravitational force
would normally scale with the

00:13:29.428 --> 00:13:31.860
volume, [? except that it's ?]
in the surface, [INAUDIBLE].

00:13:31.860 --> 00:13:34.070
PROFESSOR: OK, so let's see.

00:13:34.070 --> 00:13:39.600
F drag proportional
to area and weight

00:13:39.600 --> 00:13:40.890
proportional to area.

00:13:40.890 --> 00:13:43.155
So that's an argument
for which choice?

00:13:43.155 --> 00:13:43.490
AUDIENCE: For C.

00:13:43.490 --> 00:13:44.740
PROFESSOR: For C, OK.

00:13:47.360 --> 00:13:50.490
How do you know that the drag
scales with the area?

00:13:50.490 --> 00:13:54.270
Maybe it scales with square
root of area.

00:13:58.350 --> 00:13:59.840
Any arguments pro or con?

00:14:05.220 --> 00:14:07.158
OK, yeah.

00:14:07.158 --> 00:14:09.553
AUDIENCE: You could argue that
it scales with the area

00:14:09.553 --> 00:14:13.385
because then you just break
it up into decimal pieces.

00:14:13.385 --> 00:14:15.780
Each one has the same
force intensity.

00:14:15.780 --> 00:14:21.600
PROFESSOR: OK, so for this,
let's say there's a thought

00:14:21.600 --> 00:14:22.830
experiment of subdividing.

