00:27:13.640 --> 00:27:15.320
You will be annoyed.

00:27:15.320 --> 00:27:19.020
So it doesn't help you to
actually say how annoyed you

00:27:19.020 --> 00:27:21.280
are and really make that
person feel terrible.

00:27:21.280 --> 00:27:23.690
Because then what you've done
is you've polarized the

00:27:23.690 --> 00:27:25.410
audience against yourself
besides making

00:27:25.410 --> 00:27:27.440
that person feel bad.

00:27:27.440 --> 00:27:30.250
So it's much better to do what
I did, which was say,

00:27:30.250 --> 00:27:30.960
OK, tell you what.

00:27:30.960 --> 00:27:34.560
I'll answer your
question later.

00:27:34.560 --> 00:27:37.210
But also what I tried to do
is answer it implicitly.

00:27:37.210 --> 00:27:40.140
I don't know if you noticed, but
what I did was when I came

00:27:40.140 --> 00:27:43.010
to ask people, I figured, OK, so
people sort of have an idea

00:27:43.010 --> 00:27:46.140
that it should be C just because
of somebody said,

00:27:46.140 --> 00:27:48.860
well, I've seen the
demonstration before.

00:27:48.860 --> 00:27:52.580
But what I wanted to know was
not why you think C is right

00:27:52.580 --> 00:27:55.450
but why you think any of them
could be plausible.

00:27:55.450 --> 00:27:58.860
So that was always part of the
question, but I emphasized

00:27:58.860 --> 00:28:00.840
that part more.

00:28:00.840 --> 00:28:07.440
And it has a good educational
purpose, which is that you're

00:28:07.440 --> 00:28:09.840
trying to predict not just what
the quote "right answer"

00:28:09.840 --> 00:28:11.820
is, but you're trying
to expand your

00:28:11.820 --> 00:28:12.960
repertoire of options.

00:28:12.960 --> 00:28:14.900
So you're actually making
yourself more creative by

00:28:14.900 --> 00:28:16.950
thinking, what could
be plausible?

00:28:16.950 --> 00:28:19.350
Because it's that way of
thinking that you're able to

00:28:19.350 --> 00:28:20.400
use in other problems.

00:28:20.400 --> 00:28:24.460
So I tried to turn it around a
bit and push it in a direction

00:28:24.460 --> 00:28:27.860
that it would still be a useful
discussion for people.

00:28:27.860 --> 00:28:30.880
OK, maybe not as useful as if
people didn't know ahead of

00:28:30.880 --> 00:28:34.850
time that the answer is C,
but still a useful one.

00:28:34.850 --> 00:28:38.450
Does that help answer
your question?

00:28:38.450 --> 00:28:42.360
OK, so now what we've done--
we've actually gone through a

00:28:42.360 --> 00:28:43.550
whole teaching example.

00:28:43.550 --> 00:28:45.094
Yes, question.

00:28:45.094 --> 00:28:47.529
AUDIENCE: So [INAUDIBLE]

00:28:47.529 --> 00:28:51.055
talk about when you're writing
down the number of votes, if

00:28:51.055 --> 00:28:53.170
you should leave them actually
like [INAUDIBLE].

00:29:00.140 --> 00:29:01.050
PROFESSOR: I didn't see.

00:29:01.050 --> 00:29:01.850
That's a good point.

00:29:01.850 --> 00:29:03.582
AUDIENCE: And so that way, those
people would be like, oh

00:29:03.582 --> 00:29:04.740
my God you didn't see me.

00:29:04.740 --> 00:29:06.600
PROFESSOR: This is
a good point.

00:29:06.600 --> 00:29:07.230
And I didn't.

00:29:07.230 --> 00:29:09.540
And partly, it's because
the lighting in

00:29:09.540 --> 00:29:10.960
this room is ghastly.

00:29:10.960 --> 00:29:12.720
Partly my eyes are
not very good.

00:29:12.720 --> 00:29:15.370
But all of those reasons support
exactly what you said,

00:29:15.370 --> 00:29:20.850
which is that, especially if you
have a few people in the

00:29:20.850 --> 00:29:23.440
class, you can always get
away with adding one.

00:29:23.440 --> 00:29:24.980
And another thing you
can do is you can

00:29:24.980 --> 00:29:28.250
always add one for yourself.

00:29:28.250 --> 00:29:30.390
You think, well, I actually have
a plausible reason for

00:29:30.390 --> 00:29:30.830
one of these.

00:29:30.830 --> 00:29:33.660
Well, I'm going to vote
for one of them.

00:29:33.660 --> 00:29:36.290
And every once in a while, you
vote for a correct answer--

00:29:36.290 --> 00:29:38.280
you know, one out
of five times.

00:29:38.280 --> 00:29:39.460
So the class learns.

00:29:39.460 --> 00:29:42.160
But generally, you vote sort
of randomly just to give

00:29:42.160 --> 00:29:44.480
support to the various
answers.

00:29:44.480 --> 00:29:45.770
So you're right.

00:29:45.770 --> 00:29:49.130
The question was, is it better
to not use zip ever?

00:29:49.130 --> 00:29:50.160
And generally, it's true.

00:29:50.160 --> 00:29:52.690
Unless you're dead sure no
one voted for anything.

00:29:52.690 --> 00:29:55.530
And it's hard to see
in a large class.

00:29:55.530 --> 00:29:57.800
That's one of the advantages
of the clickers.

00:29:57.800 --> 00:29:59.910
There's disadvantages and
advantages of clickers.

00:29:59.910 --> 00:30:01.670
And we can talk about them.

00:30:01.670 --> 00:30:02.470
But you're right.

00:30:02.470 --> 00:30:04.220
One way to mitigate that--

00:30:04.220 --> 00:30:07.120
just throw in an extra vote.

00:30:07.120 --> 00:30:08.370
Other questions?

00:30:10.820 --> 00:30:12.740
So as I promised, what we're
going to do with

00:30:12.740 --> 00:30:14.150
this example is now--

00:30:14.150 --> 00:30:18.110
because this is actually not
an aerodynamics class.

00:30:18.110 --> 00:30:21.130
You may be surprised
to find out now.

00:30:21.130 --> 00:30:23.350
So you may have thought the
purpose was to actually learn

00:30:23.350 --> 00:30:24.830
the air resistance formula.

00:30:24.830 --> 00:30:26.540
If you do learn that, that's
really useful.

00:30:26.540 --> 00:30:29.270
And I'd be really happy, because
it's a great result

00:30:29.270 --> 00:30:32.260
which is very, very, very
hard to derive in pretty

00:30:32.260 --> 00:30:34.042
much any other way.

00:30:34.042 --> 00:30:37.030
You certainly can't derive
it from scratch from the

00:30:37.030 --> 00:30:38.080
Navier-Stokes equations.

00:30:38.080 --> 00:30:41.460
At least no one with current
mathematical knowledge knows

00:30:41.460 --> 00:30:42.920
how to do that.

00:30:42.920 --> 00:30:47.480
So experiment really is one of
the main ways of doing that.

00:30:47.480 --> 00:30:49.460
So it's a great result
for that.

00:30:49.460 --> 00:30:53.420
But what I want to use it for is
deconstructing it, looking

00:30:53.420 --> 00:30:57.810
at the way it was taught
and why all the things

00:30:57.810 --> 00:30:59.700
were done that way.

00:30:59.700 --> 00:31:03.930
So in that discussion will come
out general principles

00:31:03.930 --> 00:31:07.240
that we'll use throughout the
semester in all of our

00:31:07.240 --> 00:31:09.680
examples of how to do teaching,
like for example,

00:31:09.680 --> 00:31:12.320
how to make a lecture, how
to design a course.

00:31:12.320 --> 00:31:17.270
So as always, those principles
are not very effective if I

00:31:17.270 --> 00:31:18.640
just say, well, here are the
principles, and we're

00:31:18.640 --> 00:31:19.040
going to use them.

00:31:19.040 --> 00:31:20.820
It's much better if we actually
try them out in

00:31:20.820 --> 00:31:25.290
example and see where did they
show up by constructing them.

00:31:25.290 --> 00:31:31.420
So the question for the next
portion of this session is to

00:31:31.420 --> 00:31:35.980
identify all of the teaching
elements in this.

00:31:35.980 --> 00:31:37.700
So for example, what's
a teaching element?

00:31:37.700 --> 00:31:41.630
Well, for example, there
was a vote or there

00:31:41.630 --> 00:31:43.660
was a second vote.

00:31:43.660 --> 00:31:47.260
So just deconstruct it to as
fine a granularity as seems

00:31:47.260 --> 00:31:52.510
reasonable, and say, OK, this
was done, or this happened.

00:31:52.510 --> 00:31:54.500
And then, why?

00:31:54.500 --> 00:31:55.750
So two questions--

00:31:55.750 --> 00:31:57.130
do a two-column table.

00:32:02.500 --> 00:32:04.550
What and why?

00:32:04.550 --> 00:32:07.200
And there'll be a pretty long
list because there was quite a

00:32:07.200 --> 00:32:09.740
lot of things done.

00:32:09.740 --> 00:32:12.030
So find a neighbor
or two again.

00:32:12.030 --> 00:32:13.490
We'll discuss the
what and why.

00:32:13.490 --> 00:32:18.602
And then I'll clump the
whys into principles.

00:32:18.602 --> 00:32:22.680
So any questions about
that question?

00:32:22.680 --> 00:32:25.660
ANNOUNCER: Due to technical
difficulties, the rest of

00:32:25.660 --> 00:32:28.400
lecture one is unavailable.

00:32:28.400 --> 00:32:31.690
What follows is a summary of the
material presented in the

00:32:31.690 --> 00:32:33.005
remaining part of the lecture.

00:32:35.970 --> 00:32:40.520
PROFESSOR: Think back to the
question about the cones--

00:32:40.520 --> 00:32:44.470
which fell faster, or were they
the same speed, the big

00:32:44.470 --> 00:32:49.490
cone or the small cone, and how
that question was asked.

00:32:49.490 --> 00:32:53.000
What were all the elements
in the way the

00:32:53.000 --> 00:32:54.610
question was asked?

00:32:54.610 --> 00:32:55.680
What was discussed?

00:32:55.680 --> 00:32:58.800
What did you do?

00:32:58.800 --> 00:33:02.000
So it was scripted
very carefully.

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:06.670
And there were reasons for the
elements of the script.

00:33:06.670 --> 00:33:09.600
So we've had a chance
to think about that.

00:33:09.600 --> 00:33:13.890
And let me list many of these
scripting elements and their

00:33:13.890 --> 00:33:15.140
reasons for them.

00:33:26.180 --> 00:33:29.710
So on the left side, I'll
list the elements.

00:33:29.710 --> 00:33:33.530
For example, there was
lots of interaction.

00:33:33.530 --> 00:33:35.600
You were talking
to each other.

00:33:35.600 --> 00:33:36.850
You were asking questions.

00:33:46.370 --> 00:33:47.880
In fact, you weren't just
asking questions.

00:33:47.880 --> 00:33:49.770
You were voting.

00:33:49.770 --> 00:33:51.870
So twice you voted.

00:33:57.730 --> 00:33:59.040
So voting twice, discussing.

00:34:06.770 --> 00:34:08.340
So what are the reasons
for that?

00:34:08.340 --> 00:34:11.360
What are the educational
principles behind designing a

00:34:11.360 --> 00:34:15.139
question that allows lots
of interaction, voting,

00:34:15.139 --> 00:34:17.550
discussing?

00:34:17.550 --> 00:34:18.800
Well, first of all--

00:34:22.389 --> 00:34:24.360
the why--

00:34:24.360 --> 00:34:27.957
it gives the teacher, it gives
me, an idea of how the class

00:34:27.957 --> 00:34:29.207
is thinking.

00:34:49.909 --> 00:34:53.880
If, for example, I ask a
question, and in the first

00:34:53.880 --> 00:34:58.320
vote almost everyone gets it
right, I know, OK, everyone

00:34:58.320 --> 00:35:02.620
pretty much understands this
idea or this concept.

00:35:02.620 --> 00:35:05.520
I can spend very little extra
time on it and move on to

00:35:05.520 --> 00:35:08.370
something that may be more
confusing or more problematic.

00:35:08.370 --> 00:35:12.180
Whereas if most people get it
wrong, I know, OK, either the

00:35:12.180 --> 00:35:13.470
book was confusing or what I

00:35:13.470 --> 00:35:15.440
explained already was confusing.

00:35:15.440 --> 00:35:19.160
And we need to spend more time
discussing the core idea here.

00:35:19.160 --> 00:35:21.290
So it gives me instant
feedback about

00:35:21.290 --> 00:35:22.140
where the class is.

00:35:22.140 --> 00:35:25.520
I don't have to wait till the
end of the term to find out on

00:35:25.520 --> 00:35:27.330
the final exam, oh, no
one understood that.

00:35:27.330 --> 00:35:29.230
I know right there when
I have a chance to do

00:35:29.230 --> 00:35:30.480
something about it.

00:35:33.570 --> 00:35:37.390
The voting also has
another benefit.

00:35:37.390 --> 00:35:39.700
So the first benefit
is it tells me.

00:35:39.700 --> 00:35:44.060
Also, it makes this students
form a public commitment.

00:35:56.870 --> 00:36:01.000
And that public commitment has
a strong benefit, which is

00:36:01.000 --> 00:36:04.020
that the students become much
more involved in learning what

00:36:04.020 --> 00:36:06.330
the outcome of the
discussion is.

00:36:06.330 --> 00:36:08.470
Because they've actually made
a public commitment to one

00:36:08.470 --> 00:36:10.465
choice or another choice.

00:36:10.465 --> 00:36:12.485
So it increases the level
of engagement.

00:36:15.540 --> 00:36:17.250
Similarly, it creates tension.

00:36:17.250 --> 00:36:20.060
People want to know what's
going to happen.

00:36:20.060 --> 00:36:23.190
So when the demonstration
is actually done--

00:36:23.190 --> 00:36:26.090
the final decider is
the experiment--

00:36:26.090 --> 00:36:27.990
everyone is paying very,
very close attention.

00:36:31.800 --> 00:36:33.820
So I'll say not just tension,
but I'll say it creates

00:36:33.820 --> 00:36:35.070
dramatic tension.

00:36:46.540 --> 00:36:51.160
Furthermore, the chance for lots
of interaction increases

00:36:51.160 --> 00:36:55.460
the amount of interaction
in the whole class.

00:36:55.460 --> 00:36:58.300
For example, students will ask
questions much more easily if

00:36:58.300 --> 00:37:00.780
they've already had a chance
to discuss their ideas in

00:37:00.780 --> 00:37:02.030
small groups.

00:37:13.500 --> 00:37:18.020
So that's one set of elements
and the educational reasons

00:37:18.020 --> 00:37:21.550
for building those in to how one
asks questions in class.

00:37:30.980 --> 00:37:36.460
Another one is that I used a
physical object, in an actual

00:37:36.460 --> 00:37:39.510
demonstration, so these cones.

00:37:39.510 --> 00:37:43.740
And the physical object
is also cheap.

00:37:43.740 --> 00:37:44.720
Anyone can make those.

00:37:44.720 --> 00:37:47.570
You just cut circles out of
paper, cut a quarter away, and

00:37:47.570 --> 00:37:48.180
tape it together.

00:37:48.180 --> 00:37:49.430
You have a cone.

00:38:01.630 --> 00:38:03.140
What are the benefits of that?

00:38:03.140 --> 00:38:07.450
Well, first, it's much more
convincing than if I just do a

00:38:07.450 --> 00:38:10.830
derivation from the
Navier-Stokes equations or

00:38:10.830 --> 00:38:12.620
however one gets
to the result.

00:38:12.620 --> 00:38:16.470
And say, OK, well, therefore
the drag is proportional to

00:38:16.470 --> 00:38:17.830
the square of the speed.

00:38:17.830 --> 00:38:20.350
Or therefore, they all fall
at the same speed

00:38:20.350 --> 00:38:21.770
whatever their size.

00:38:21.770 --> 00:38:24.410
If I just say that, or even if
I prove it with equations,

00:38:24.410 --> 00:38:27.110
that's not nearly as convincing
as seeing it

00:38:27.110 --> 00:38:28.360
actually happen.

00:38:38.480 --> 00:38:41.110
And that's where in terms of
being convincing, it's also

00:38:41.110 --> 00:38:44.180
important that the demonstration
be cheap.

00:38:44.180 --> 00:38:47.290
If, for example, to see it
actually happen requires

00:38:47.290 --> 00:38:49.620
$100,000 of equipment--

00:38:49.620 --> 00:38:53.050
well, who knows what happens in
that $100,000 of equipment

00:38:53.050 --> 00:38:55.740
and sensors and test devices
and whatnot.

00:38:55.740 --> 00:38:58.320
Whereas if it's a cheap piece
of paper you can cut out for

00:38:58.320 --> 00:39:02.320
$0.02, well, then anyone can
try it themself, too.

00:39:02.320 --> 00:39:06.410
And it's not so mediated by
lots of sensory devices.

00:39:06.410 --> 00:39:08.590
It's much more immediate.

00:39:08.590 --> 00:39:09.640
It's much more convincing.

00:39:09.640 --> 00:39:11.370
So I'll say here in
parentheses, a

00:39:11.370 --> 00:39:12.647
cheap physical object--

00:39:15.990 --> 00:39:17.240
ideally, if possible.

00:39:20.070 --> 00:39:24.130
Furthermore, the physical object
actually connects the

00:39:24.130 --> 00:39:26.920
mathematical and physical and
engineering ideas to the

00:39:26.920 --> 00:39:28.170
physical world.

00:39:41.480 --> 00:39:44.220
In the end, we want to try to
understand how the world

00:39:44.220 --> 00:39:45.880
works, maybe put it
back together

00:39:45.880 --> 00:39:48.300
in ways of our choosing.

00:39:48.300 --> 00:39:52.910
So purely living in the
formal world, we're

00:39:52.910 --> 00:39:54.160
living in the clouds.

00:39:54.160 --> 00:39:56.360
By bringing in a physical
object, we actually put our

00:39:56.360 --> 00:39:57.750
feet on the ground as well.

00:40:05.320 --> 00:40:10.270
Another part of the
demonstration of the script

00:40:10.270 --> 00:40:13.930
was various things that might
have seemed extraneous.

00:40:13.930 --> 00:40:19.430
For example, I mentioned that
I hope my socks were matched

00:40:19.430 --> 00:40:20.720
well when I stood
on the table.

00:40:28.660 --> 00:40:30.120
I also discussed--

00:40:30.120 --> 00:40:32.320
when I was standing on the
table, I said, OK, I need the

00:40:32.320 --> 00:40:35.360
class's help here because I
don't have depth perception.

00:40:35.360 --> 00:40:39.300
So I can't tell when
I'm dropping them--

00:40:39.300 --> 00:40:43.230
when I was dropping one cone
versus four cones, I can't

00:40:43.230 --> 00:40:47.270
tell when I've got this one
twice as high as this one.

00:40:47.270 --> 00:40:48.700
And so you need to tell me.

00:40:48.700 --> 00:40:51.920
So I talked about my failing
in the depth perception

00:40:51.920 --> 00:40:53.170
department.

00:41:02.020 --> 00:41:04.200
So both of these might
seem extraneous to

00:41:04.200 --> 00:41:05.320
engineering and science.

00:41:05.320 --> 00:41:08.620
But actually, they have a sound
educational reason.

00:41:08.620 --> 00:41:13.600
So the socks joke-- well, that
makes the teacher seem much

00:41:13.600 --> 00:41:14.850
more human.

00:41:28.190 --> 00:41:30.670
Similarly, for the lack
of depth perception--

00:41:30.670 --> 00:41:32.910
oh, well, the teacher
has flaws, too.

00:41:32.910 --> 00:41:35.080
They're not this perfect person
who seems to know

00:41:35.080 --> 00:41:35.960
everything.

00:41:35.960 --> 00:41:38.910
And in fact, that one,
specifically because I didn't

00:41:38.910 --> 00:41:41.390
have depth perception, I needed
the help of the class.

00:41:41.390 --> 00:41:44.760
So that, again, is an excuse
to involve the whole class.

00:41:44.760 --> 00:41:48.625
So no depth perception makes
a teacher human is also an

00:41:48.625 --> 00:41:49.970
excuse for more engagement.

00:42:06.880 --> 00:42:11.900
And related to discussing
another element of the script,

00:42:11.900 --> 00:42:15.370
I want to amplify this one
up there, the discussing.

00:42:15.370 --> 00:42:17.350
And I'll put it back
down here.

00:42:17.350 --> 00:42:22.410
The discussion happened first
by yourself, then in a small

00:42:22.410 --> 00:42:26.830
group, and then in the whole
class together where people

00:42:26.830 --> 00:42:28.080
were suggesting reasons.

00:42:43.240 --> 00:42:45.620
So I'll say discussions
at several scales--

00:42:45.620 --> 00:42:50.445
self, group, and class.

00:42:57.880 --> 00:43:01.080
So what's the educational
purpose of that?

00:43:01.080 --> 00:43:03.940
Well, I mentioned one purpose
up there, which is it

00:43:03.940 --> 00:43:05.780
increases questions.

00:43:05.780 --> 00:43:07.920
And that's certainly true.

00:43:07.920 --> 00:43:11.830
Another one is by allowing
people to think for themselves

00:43:11.830 --> 00:43:17.020
first, you're giving space for
what's called the introverts.

00:43:17.020 --> 00:43:20.020
Some people like lots of time
to think for themselves, and

00:43:20.020 --> 00:43:23.030
only then do they want to
share with other people.

00:43:23.030 --> 00:43:25.330
Because otherwise, their
thoughts get derailed by what

00:43:25.330 --> 00:43:26.440
everybody else is saying.

00:43:26.440 --> 00:43:28.750
Some people don't know what
they're thinking till they

00:43:28.750 --> 00:43:29.910
talk to other people.

00:43:29.910 --> 00:43:31.290
Let's call them the
extroverts.

00:43:31.290 --> 00:43:36.170
So by allowing space for self
talk and group talk, you're

00:43:36.170 --> 00:43:37.845
teaching to the introverts
and the extroverts.

00:43:37.845 --> 00:43:41.460
So you're matching to the
learning styles of different

00:43:41.460 --> 00:43:42.710
students in the class.

00:44:01.570 --> 00:44:05.510
And then by scaling it up slowly
from self to group to

00:44:05.510 --> 00:44:08.670
class, you make it safe.

00:44:08.670 --> 00:44:12.380
You make it not a huge
transition to start to go to

00:44:12.380 --> 00:44:13.410
the next stage.

00:44:13.410 --> 00:44:15.980
Whereas if I just ask the
question of the class, OK,

00:44:15.980 --> 00:44:17.880
whole class, now, you tell me
what you think about this

00:44:17.880 --> 00:44:22.280
question and I skipped these
parts, only the usual suspects

00:44:22.280 --> 00:44:25.410
would be offering
me ideas here.

00:44:25.410 --> 00:44:27.340
The people who always raise
their hand-- maybe they sit in

00:44:27.340 --> 00:44:28.170
the front row.

00:44:28.170 --> 00:44:32.160
Whereas by allowing people to
think for themselves, then

00:44:32.160 --> 00:44:34.250
discuss in a group the ideas
that they thought for

00:44:34.250 --> 00:44:36.890
themselves, check out what
they've done there.

00:44:36.890 --> 00:44:39.040
If they still think they don't
understand something and no

00:44:39.040 --> 00:44:41.260
one in the group understood it,
then they feel safe asking

00:44:41.260 --> 00:44:42.220
the whole class.

00:44:42.220 --> 00:44:44.720
We're actually building
a bridge for people to

00:44:44.720 --> 00:44:47.840
participate in the
large group.

00:44:47.840 --> 00:44:50.120
So again, that point's
up there.

00:44:50.120 --> 00:44:52.280
But it's so important I'm
putting it down here, too.

00:44:56.930 --> 00:45:01.730
So I'll call it builds a
bridge to collective

00:45:01.730 --> 00:45:02.980
participation.

00:45:11.320 --> 00:45:14.320
And that participation can be
people contributing ideas or

00:45:14.320 --> 00:45:16.065
questions which are
themselves ideas.

00:45:22.160 --> 00:45:28.490
Another feature of how the whole
thing was done was that

00:45:28.490 --> 00:45:32.700
I walked around a fair amount.

00:45:32.700 --> 00:45:35.230
I used a lot of the space.

00:45:35.230 --> 00:45:37.270
For example, even some of
the vertical space,

00:45:37.270 --> 00:45:38.840
standing on the table.

00:45:38.840 --> 00:45:43.080
Moving over here, moving over
there to make sure I heard the

00:45:43.080 --> 00:45:44.565
question from that side
of the class.

00:45:49.070 --> 00:45:51.975
So filling the lecture space.

00:46:00.380 --> 00:46:02.290
Well, what's the educational
reason for that?

00:46:02.290 --> 00:46:07.030
Well, in a way it's the opposite
of the socks joke.

00:46:09.840 --> 00:46:11.200
In one way, it's the opposite.

00:46:11.200 --> 00:46:12.170
In another way, it's the same.

00:46:12.170 --> 00:46:14.620
It's showing that the teacher is
human and that teaching is

00:46:14.620 --> 00:46:16.390
a human activity.

00:46:16.390 --> 00:46:20.570
This is what actors
do on stage.

00:46:20.570 --> 00:46:23.460
The stage, the whole stage
is there for a reason.

00:46:23.460 --> 00:46:25.440
And the actors will
use all of it.

00:46:25.440 --> 00:46:28.170
They won't just stand in the
middle the whole time, except

00:46:28.170 --> 00:46:31.565
for rare comedy monologues
or monologues.

00:46:31.565 --> 00:46:33.550
But otherwise, all the
pieces of the stage

00:46:33.550 --> 00:46:34.410
are there for a reason.

00:46:34.410 --> 00:46:35.310
And the actors use it.

00:46:35.310 --> 00:46:37.560
They make that space
their own space.

00:46:37.560 --> 00:46:39.550
They fill the lecture
room space.

00:46:39.550 --> 00:46:42.870
So as a teacher, you want to
do that because that shows

00:46:42.870 --> 00:46:44.310
that this is your space.

00:46:44.310 --> 00:46:45.660
You're comfortable there.

00:46:45.660 --> 00:46:47.725
And it increases your
credibility with the students.

00:47:02.240 --> 00:47:06.530
And similar to this, it brings
in students from all parts of

00:47:06.530 --> 00:47:08.880
the classroom, especially
if it's a big classroom.

00:47:08.880 --> 00:47:11.830
They all feel somehow connected
to what's going on.

00:47:11.830 --> 00:47:14.580
Because you haven't just stood
in one corner of the room or

00:47:14.580 --> 00:47:18.820
just paid attention to one
section of the class.

00:47:18.820 --> 00:47:22.720
So in one way, it's the opposite
of the socks joke.

00:47:22.720 --> 00:47:25.890
Because in that way, the
teacher is being a bit

00:47:25.890 --> 00:47:26.810
self-deprecating.

00:47:26.810 --> 00:47:29.510
Here, the lecturer is acting
very confident

00:47:29.510 --> 00:47:30.790
by filling the space.

00:47:30.790 --> 00:47:32.370
But in another way,
it's the same.

00:47:32.370 --> 00:47:37.590
They're both playing on the
human part of teaching, which

00:47:37.590 --> 00:47:38.990
is inescapable.

00:47:38.990 --> 00:47:41.370
And if it's neglected, the
teaching falls flat.

00:47:44.570 --> 00:47:48.510
And finally, there was one other
point which may seem

00:47:48.510 --> 00:47:50.690
like a mechanical point.

00:47:50.690 --> 00:47:53.650
But it's so useful that
I'll put it here, too.

00:47:53.650 --> 00:47:57.370
And I'll write it
with big chalk.

00:47:57.370 --> 00:48:04.750
Point is, I wrote everything on
the board using big chalk.

00:48:04.750 --> 00:48:06.920
And why is that important?

00:48:06.920 --> 00:48:10.210
Well, in a small classroom of
maybe 10 or 15 people, it

00:48:10.210 --> 00:48:10.980
probably doesn't matter.

00:48:10.980 --> 00:48:12.310
Everyone can read everything.

00:48:12.310 --> 00:48:16.480
But if it's at all a large
classroom, people can't read

00:48:16.480 --> 00:48:17.940
the writing way in the back.

00:48:17.940 --> 00:48:19.840
By using big chalk,
you increase the

00:48:19.840 --> 00:48:21.090
signal to noise ratio.

00:48:31.380 --> 00:48:34.680
Now, that may not seem
so important when

00:48:34.680 --> 00:48:35.750
you first think about.

00:48:35.750 --> 00:48:37.480
The reason being is
that you already

00:48:37.480 --> 00:48:38.980
know what you're writing.

00:48:38.980 --> 00:48:45.720
So even if you see really thin
lines, something that's not

00:48:45.720 --> 00:48:49.720
very clearly written, you still
know what it should say.

00:48:49.720 --> 00:48:51.250
And you just read
it correctly.

00:48:51.250 --> 00:48:53.350
But the students, on
the other hand--

00:48:53.350 --> 00:48:55.670
they don't have the knowledge
that you have.

00:48:55.670 --> 00:48:59.890
So they can't error-correct
any--

00:48:59.890 --> 00:49:02.070
fill in the missing
gaps in the lines.

00:49:02.070 --> 00:49:06.450
They need as much signal as
possible to really copy down

00:49:06.450 --> 00:49:09.410
anything correctly, to make sure
that they're not adding

00:49:09.410 --> 00:49:12.030
noise onto the signal that
you're trying to get across.

00:49:12.030 --> 00:49:16.210
So in some ways, a small point,
but in other ways, an

00:49:16.210 --> 00:49:16.860
important point.

00:49:16.860 --> 00:49:19.750
Because if you don't do it,
you'll throw away most of your

00:49:19.750 --> 00:49:24.270
other benefits because the
students will actually be

00:49:24.270 --> 00:49:27.320
incorporating wrong information,
just errors, just

00:49:27.320 --> 00:49:29.180
by mistake without
even realizing.

00:49:29.180 --> 00:49:30.970
And the big chalk can actually
minimize that.

00:49:30.970 --> 00:49:33.410
So just a mechanical point.

00:49:33.410 --> 00:49:37.615
I always keep pieces of big
chalk in my backpack.

00:49:37.615 --> 00:49:40.700
And wherever I happen to be
teaching, I can always pull

00:49:40.700 --> 00:49:42.320
them out and use them.

00:49:42.320 --> 00:49:45.010
Because you will find many
classrooms only have standard

00:49:45.010 --> 00:49:46.420
chalk provided.

00:49:46.420 --> 00:49:48.940
And the big chalk is something
you have to do yourself.

00:49:48.940 --> 00:49:53.270
So just carry a few pieces
with you as you need.

00:49:53.270 --> 00:49:57.410
So those are some of
the many scripting

00:49:57.410 --> 00:50:01.610
elements in this example.

00:50:01.610 --> 00:50:05.320
And you'll see a similar
example in a subsequent

00:50:05.320 --> 00:50:08.040
lecture, in the lecture on
teaching interactively, which

00:50:08.040 --> 00:50:09.280
is lecture six.

00:50:09.280 --> 00:50:12.830
And you'll see some of these
points come up again and some

00:50:12.830 --> 00:50:15.710
of these reasons discussed again
in a different example.

00:50:15.710 --> 00:50:20.000
So you'll have two different
engineering examples, but done

00:50:20.000 --> 00:50:20.890
in a similar way.

00:50:20.890 --> 00:50:24.910
And you can see the scripting
elements and how they're

00:50:24.910 --> 00:50:26.790
different and how they're the
same in both examples.

00:50:26.790 --> 00:50:30.330
And see which ones you can
use in your own teaching.

00:50:30.330 --> 00:50:35.910
So now, from these scripting
elements, we've extracted

00:50:35.910 --> 00:50:37.910
teaching principles.

00:50:37.910 --> 00:50:40.490
So credibility, signal
to noise ratio--

00:50:40.490 --> 00:50:42.360
just remember those.

00:50:42.360 --> 00:50:46.320
And then here's a bunch more.

00:50:46.320 --> 00:50:50.310
I want to summarize them,
extract the main highlights

00:50:50.310 --> 00:50:54.800
from that so that you can come
away with a clean picture of

00:50:54.800 --> 00:50:59.770
what to watch for throughout
this semester.

00:50:59.770 --> 00:51:03.270
So the main themes of
all of these are--

00:51:13.650 --> 00:51:15.880
I would say they fall into
three categories.

00:51:15.880 --> 00:51:16.820
Let me list them.

00:51:16.820 --> 00:51:19.100
And then I'll break them
into three categories.

00:51:19.100 --> 00:51:27.855
There's ways to promote
questions and discussion.

00:51:33.660 --> 00:51:36.230
There's using stories
and humor.

00:51:43.560 --> 00:51:48.260
And demos and, related to that,
things you can see--

00:51:48.260 --> 00:51:49.630
visual examples.

00:51:57.260 --> 00:52:02.040
And another pair of
environments--

00:52:02.040 --> 00:52:03.290
credibility--

00:52:07.480 --> 00:52:09.310
filling the lecture space--

00:52:09.310 --> 00:52:15.650
and what I haven't directly said
yet as such, but we'll

00:52:15.650 --> 00:52:22.150
call it a safe environment
for learning.

00:52:22.150 --> 00:52:24.160
Creating a safe environment
for learning.

00:52:24.160 --> 00:52:28.490
That's what discussion at
several scales enables.

00:52:28.490 --> 00:52:30.710
You create a safe environment
for people to think for

00:52:30.710 --> 00:52:33.960
themselves, which then makes it
safe for them to think in a

00:52:33.960 --> 00:52:36.490
group and discuss in group,
which then makes it safe for

00:52:36.490 --> 00:52:40.050
them to think in
a whole class.

00:52:40.050 --> 00:52:44.420
And so that makes safe bridge,
or two bridges, towards

00:52:44.420 --> 00:52:46.260
collective participation.

00:52:46.260 --> 00:52:50.540
So you've made a safe learning
and questioning environment.

00:52:50.540 --> 00:52:53.750
Without this environment,
that won't happen.

00:52:53.750 --> 00:52:56.740
So I put these in three columns
because I think they

00:52:56.740 --> 00:53:01.630
fall into sort of three
pieces of the brain.

00:53:01.630 --> 00:53:02.880
Questions and discussion--

00:53:05.510 --> 00:53:06.760
sort of left brain.

00:53:09.470 --> 00:53:19.990
Stories, humor, demos, and
visual-- that's right brain.

00:53:19.990 --> 00:53:22.360
And credibility and a
safe environment--

00:53:22.360 --> 00:53:31.240
I'll call that the emotional
brain, the amygdala.

00:53:31.240 --> 00:53:34.910
Maybe you could put humor
over there, as well.

00:53:34.910 --> 00:53:37.800
But the reason I put preamble
stories with the right brain

00:53:37.800 --> 00:53:41.770
is it's a different kind of
learning than we think of when

00:53:41.770 --> 00:53:43.560
we think of left-brain learning,
for example,

00:53:43.560 --> 00:53:47.990
learning an analytical method
or the sequence

00:53:47.990 --> 00:53:49.740
of steps or a recipe.

00:53:49.740 --> 00:53:52.140
The learning that happens
from stories--

00:53:52.140 --> 00:53:55.260
for example, about the
depth perception--

00:53:55.260 --> 00:53:56.110
is a different kind.

00:53:56.110 --> 00:53:57.930
It's kind of implicit
in a way, more

00:53:57.930 --> 00:53:59.810
perceptive and the holistic.

00:53:59.810 --> 00:54:01.810
So I put it in the right-brain
category.

00:54:01.810 --> 00:54:06.610
So these are main themes in
creating your own classroom

00:54:06.610 --> 00:54:09.370
teaching environment
and structuring how

00:54:09.370 --> 00:54:10.520
you're going to teach.

00:54:10.520 --> 00:54:15.140
And sure, there's also all
the questions of content.

00:54:15.140 --> 00:54:18.060
But the reason I'm focusing on
all of these is that the

00:54:18.060 --> 00:54:19.990
questions of content--

00:54:19.990 --> 00:54:22.220
those have been done so
many, so many times.

00:54:22.220 --> 00:54:23.890
You can find all the
content in a

00:54:23.890 --> 00:54:25.630
gazillion different textbooks.

00:54:25.630 --> 00:54:27.320
But the question is, how do
you integrate all of that

00:54:27.320 --> 00:54:30.990
content into something
that makes for

00:54:30.990 --> 00:54:32.390
good student learning?

00:54:32.390 --> 00:54:35.990
And to do that, you need to take
account of all this, all

00:54:35.990 --> 00:54:39.030
of these features, all these
aspects of the brain.

00:54:39.030 --> 00:54:42.540
Because humans are
not computers.

00:54:42.540 --> 00:54:45.490
And they can't just learn
by being programmed.

00:54:45.490 --> 00:54:54.740
So from all these themes,
extract one giant theme, which

00:54:54.740 --> 00:55:03.527
is that teaching is not
necessarily equal to learning.

00:55:06.390 --> 00:55:10.820
Just standing up there and
teaching stuff is no guarantee

00:55:10.820 --> 00:55:11.917
that students will learn it.

00:55:11.917 --> 00:55:15.270
You need to pay attention to all
these features, all of the

00:55:15.270 --> 00:55:17.430
human interaction to
make sure that

00:55:17.430 --> 00:55:20.160
learning actually happens.

00:55:20.160 --> 00:55:24.900
So that's, if anything,
the main theme.

00:55:24.900 --> 00:55:33.270
Or phrased another way is that
meaning and knowledge must be

00:55:33.270 --> 00:55:34.730
constructed by the learner.

00:55:50.020 --> 00:55:54.700
And all these ideas up here,
these scripting elements,

00:55:54.700 --> 00:55:58.270
these principles here are
ways to help that

00:55:58.270 --> 00:55:59.690
construction happen.

00:55:59.690 --> 00:56:01.680
Just telling them
doesn't do it.

00:56:01.680 --> 00:56:06.250
You have to enable, facilitate,
that construction.

00:56:06.250 --> 00:56:09.440
So what we're going to do for
the rest of the semester is

00:56:09.440 --> 00:56:12.720
we're going to see these
principles, these principles,

00:56:12.720 --> 00:56:17.705
these boiled-down themes, this
idea, this large idea--

00:56:23.550 --> 00:56:27.370
the big idea of the entire
course exemplified in several

00:56:27.370 --> 00:56:31.230
topics and areas that are
central to teaching science

00:56:31.230 --> 00:56:32.870
and engineering and mathematics

00:56:32.870 --> 00:56:35.490
at the college level.

00:56:35.490 --> 00:56:38.460
And so the outline for
the rest of the

00:56:38.460 --> 00:56:39.750
semester is as follows.

