Today was lecture one.

00:56:44.330 --> 00:56:46.270
And that was general principles
of teaching.

00:56:55.800 --> 00:56:58.115
The next one will be on how
to teach equations.

00:57:04.640 --> 00:57:07.600
Equations are central in all
science and mathematics and

00:57:07.600 --> 00:57:08.300
engineering teaching.

00:57:08.300 --> 00:57:09.900
So how do you teach
equations--

00:57:09.900 --> 00:57:12.150
in other words, some of
the central content--

00:57:12.150 --> 00:57:14.400
taking account of all
of these ideas?

00:57:18.440 --> 00:57:20.240
Can you tell stories when
you teach equations?

00:57:20.240 --> 00:57:21.430
How can you do that?

00:57:21.430 --> 00:57:23.940
Well, we'll see.

00:57:23.940 --> 00:57:27.030
The third lecture, the third
topic, is taking account of

00:57:27.030 --> 00:57:44.270
students' misconceptions
and thereby

00:57:44.270 --> 00:57:47.390
avoiding rote learning.

00:57:47.390 --> 00:57:50.720
So you can see already where
some of the ideas that we've

00:57:50.720 --> 00:57:52.510
been talking about here are
going to help here.

00:57:52.510 --> 00:57:56.450
For example, having lots of
interaction and voting--

00:57:56.450 --> 00:57:58.050
you find out where
the students are.

00:57:58.050 --> 00:58:00.630
You'll find out if they have
funny ways of thinking about

00:58:00.630 --> 00:58:04.390
stuff, maybe even predictable
ways, but ways that don't help

00:58:04.390 --> 00:58:06.250
them actually solve problems
in the real world.

00:58:06.250 --> 00:58:08.590
Well, how do you take
account of that?

00:58:08.590 --> 00:58:11.070
There's one way right
there already.

00:58:11.070 --> 00:58:17.685
Then designing homework
and exam problems.

00:58:27.220 --> 00:58:29.140
And the fifth one is
course design.

00:58:38.370 --> 00:58:40.310
How do you structure
a whole course?

00:58:48.390 --> 00:58:49.920
Sixth one is teaching
interactively.

00:59:00.180 --> 00:59:03.200
As an example, you've already
seen one example, which is

00:59:03.200 --> 00:59:04.510
this kind of question.

00:59:04.510 --> 00:59:05.340
Well, what are the general

00:59:05.340 --> 00:59:07.350
principles behind such questions?

00:59:07.350 --> 00:59:09.760
Can you make longer versions,
shorter ones?

00:59:09.760 --> 00:59:12.380
Are there short ways of building
in interaction and

00:59:12.380 --> 00:59:13.640
questions into learning?

