01:02:46.260 --> 01:02:48.380
So in reality--

01:02:48.380 --> 01:02:52.550
one question along that line
is, what about grading?

01:02:52.550 --> 01:02:56.060
How do you actually implement
your grading policy as an

01:02:56.060 --> 01:02:59.150
assistant professor in a
traditional department?

01:02:59.150 --> 01:03:02.810
So my grading policy is
generally that, especially in

01:03:02.810 --> 01:03:07.930
a pass/fail course, that the
grading be very minimal.

01:03:07.930 --> 01:03:09.380
And in general, I think
that's a good

01:03:09.380 --> 01:03:12.650
policy for grading overall.

01:03:12.650 --> 01:03:15.300
And we can talk throughout the
semester about why and the

01:03:15.300 --> 01:03:17.160
research behind that.

01:03:17.160 --> 01:03:21.580
But how would you do that if
you're starting out new?

01:03:21.580 --> 01:03:25.650
And the general rule is there's
no right answer.

01:03:25.650 --> 01:03:28.060
For example, one solution--

01:03:28.060 --> 01:03:29.980
it's not quite the answer
to the question--

01:03:29.980 --> 01:03:33.950
is to take a position at a
place where you're the

01:03:33.950 --> 01:03:35.750
department head.

01:03:35.750 --> 01:03:40.510
So actually, I was offered a
teaching position like that

01:03:40.510 --> 01:03:41.650
after I finished graduate
school.

01:03:41.650 --> 01:03:43.300
And I thought long and
hard about it.

01:03:43.300 --> 01:03:45.970
So I would have been the head
of the physics and math

01:03:45.970 --> 01:03:47.700
department.

01:03:47.700 --> 01:03:49.570
Now, that was the good side.

01:03:49.570 --> 01:03:53.260
The bad side was that I was
the only member of both

01:03:53.260 --> 01:03:54.670
departments.

01:03:54.670 --> 01:03:56.400
And so on the one hand, I
was a department head.

01:03:56.400 --> 01:03:59.080
But also, I was the only one
doing all the teaching.

01:03:59.080 --> 01:04:01.870
And I would have only
me to boss around.

01:04:01.870 --> 01:04:05.220
But in that situation, you do
have a huge amount of freedom.

01:04:05.220 --> 01:04:08.670
And I could have done pretty
much whatever I wanted.

01:04:08.670 --> 01:04:12.130
Now, I decided not to take that
position because I really

01:04:12.130 --> 01:04:15.920
wasn't sure exactly what I
wanted to do in terms of

01:04:15.920 --> 01:04:16.740
improving teaching.

01:04:16.740 --> 01:04:18.770
And I thought, well, I really
need some more experience.

01:04:18.770 --> 01:04:22.080
And I decided to
do a post-doc.

01:04:22.080 --> 01:04:25.150
But that is one solution
to that problem.

01:04:25.150 --> 01:04:28.100
It's not a very generalizable
solution.

01:04:28.100 --> 01:04:30.220
There are not many positions
like that.

01:04:30.220 --> 01:04:37.560
Another solution is to what I
call the Clark Kent solution.

01:04:37.560 --> 01:04:42.290
So you go around as a
traditional faculty member, in

01:04:42.290 --> 01:04:44.130
the Clark Kent outfit.

01:04:44.130 --> 01:04:46.780
And then as soon as you
get tenure, foom,

01:04:46.780 --> 01:04:48.270
off comes the suit.

01:04:48.270 --> 01:04:50.430
And everyone realizes that oh,
actually, we hired someone

01:04:50.430 --> 01:04:52.830
else completely, who actually
has all these interesting

01:04:52.830 --> 01:04:54.820
ideas about teaching.

01:04:54.820 --> 01:05:01.210
So that is generally legally
protected to some extent.

01:05:01.210 --> 01:05:07.370
And you won't easily be fired,
although a colleague of mine

01:05:07.370 --> 01:05:09.150
in Canada--

01:05:09.150 --> 01:05:12.740
the university is trying
to fire him for

01:05:12.740 --> 01:05:16.440
giving all As in a course.

01:05:16.440 --> 01:05:19.350
So this does speak
to this question.

01:05:19.350 --> 01:05:20.620
And it shows it is
a tricky issue.

01:05:20.620 --> 01:05:23.450
So he believes-- and
I agree with him--

01:05:23.450 --> 01:05:27.450
that grades generally just
produce obedient people.

01:05:27.450 --> 01:05:29.850
One of their main functions is
to produce obedient people and

01:05:29.850 --> 01:05:32.620
obedient students, rather than
students who love learning and

01:05:32.620 --> 01:05:34.290
want to question.

01:05:34.290 --> 01:05:37.410
So he wanted to teach one of his
courses-- he's a tenured

01:05:37.410 --> 01:05:38.230
professor of physics.

01:05:38.230 --> 01:05:40.570
He wanted to teach one of
his courses pass/fail.

01:05:40.570 --> 01:05:42.300
And the university said, no.

01:05:42.300 --> 01:05:45.250
By university regulations, that
course is graded only.

01:05:45.250 --> 01:05:47.120
It has to be taught
with grades.

01:05:47.120 --> 01:05:48.700
So he said, OK, fine.

01:05:48.700 --> 01:05:50.660
On the first day of class, he
just told everyone they were

01:05:50.660 --> 01:05:53.390
going to get an A+.

01:05:53.390 --> 01:05:55.590
And according to the TA--

01:05:55.590 --> 01:06:00.050
at least, this was then reported
in Canada's Globe and

01:06:00.050 --> 01:06:02.760
Mail, their sort of
New York Times--

01:06:02.760 --> 01:06:04.490
one of the teaching assistants
for the course said, yeah,

01:06:04.490 --> 01:06:07.010
there were a few students who
took advantage of that fact.

01:06:07.010 --> 01:06:12.240
But most actually did more work
and were very interested

01:06:12.240 --> 01:06:13.800
in the material because of it.

01:06:13.800 --> 01:06:16.540
So I would say, basically,
the thing was a success.

01:06:16.540 --> 01:06:19.610
And that's generally what I
find, that the less emphasis

01:06:19.610 --> 01:06:21.120
you put on grades--

01:06:21.120 --> 01:06:22.810
especially at a place
like MIT--

01:06:22.810 --> 01:06:26.620
the students' natural interest
in the material comes out.

01:06:26.620 --> 01:06:29.050
And they're more and more
willing to work and learn.

01:06:29.050 --> 01:06:30.600
And that produces long-lasting
learning.

01:06:30.600 --> 01:06:32.510
Because they're doing it for
their own reasons, not because

01:06:32.510 --> 01:06:34.450
you stood over them with
a grade and beat

01:06:34.450 --> 01:06:35.640
them over the head.

01:06:35.640 --> 01:06:38.020
So that was good.

01:06:38.020 --> 01:06:41.190
The bad part is the university
basically said, well, you're

01:06:41.190 --> 01:06:44.290
defying us, and you're going
against the purpose of the

01:06:44.290 --> 01:06:44.665
university.

01:06:44.665 --> 01:06:46.820
It's not really clear what the
purpose of the university is,

01:06:46.820 --> 01:06:49.190
except maybe to produce
obedient people.

01:06:49.190 --> 01:06:52.550
So they said, we're going to
institute proceedings for your

01:06:52.550 --> 01:06:56.850
dismissal, to strip you of
your tenure and fire you,

01:06:56.850 --> 01:06:59.550
which is a big step for
a tenured professor.

01:06:59.550 --> 01:07:02.130
And meanwhile, they banned
him from campus.

01:07:02.130 --> 01:07:05.310
So he's now not allowed on his
own university campus.

01:07:05.310 --> 01:07:08.010
So then he came to campus for
a film screening, because he

01:07:08.010 --> 01:07:10.460
runs a film series
on the campus.

01:07:10.460 --> 01:07:13.020
So he came for that,
and the university

01:07:13.020 --> 01:07:14.560
police arrested him.

01:07:14.560 --> 01:07:16.830
So he was arrested for going
to his own university.

01:07:16.830 --> 01:07:19.320
So then it got into the national
press in Canada,

01:07:19.320 --> 01:07:21.450
which doesn't make the
university look so good.

01:07:21.450 --> 01:07:24.520
But that's all by way of saying
that grading is a very

01:07:24.520 --> 01:07:27.210
touchy issue with
universities.

01:07:27.210 --> 01:07:29.690
And it's really not clear what
to do about it, because it's

01:07:29.690 --> 01:07:31.510
so embedded in the system.

01:07:31.510 --> 01:07:35.690
So I can't really offer you any
solutions to that question

01:07:35.690 --> 01:07:39.070
except to say that it's a very
tricky negotiation and you

01:07:39.070 --> 01:07:42.700
want to plan your activities
carefully.

01:07:42.700 --> 01:07:46.610
If you're going to use a lighter
grading system, don't

01:07:46.610 --> 01:07:47.760
do it all at once.

01:07:47.760 --> 01:07:52.140
Get people around you to accept
it slowly, slowly.

01:07:52.140 --> 01:07:53.860
Get students on your
side slowly.

01:07:53.860 --> 01:07:55.190
Do things slowly.

01:07:55.190 --> 01:07:59.240
Don't make any sudden moves
that get yourself fired.

01:07:59.240 --> 01:08:02.040
Work with other people
of like minds.

01:08:02.040 --> 01:08:03.960
Work together collectively.

01:08:03.960 --> 01:08:07.330
So it's not a long-term
instant solution.

01:08:07.330 --> 01:08:10.220
But any kind of social problem--
and I think grading

01:08:10.220 --> 01:08:11.330
is a social problem--

01:08:11.330 --> 01:08:14.210
doesn't have any instant
solutions.

01:08:14.210 --> 01:08:17.069
So I wanted to answer that one
first, to basically tell you

01:08:17.069 --> 01:08:19.020
that I don't have all the
answers to all the questions.

01:08:19.020 --> 01:08:23.020
And I want to give you honest
answers as far as I know them.

01:08:23.020 --> 01:08:25.170
OK, next question
about reality.

01:08:25.170 --> 01:08:27.340
You've obviously done this
many times before.

01:08:27.340 --> 01:08:29.979
As someone who needs to figure
out a logical order for the

01:08:29.979 --> 01:08:32.600
material in addition to
balancing preparation time and

01:08:32.600 --> 01:08:35.470
research, how do we juggle all
this in addition to simply

01:08:35.470 --> 01:08:37.149
focusing on style?

01:08:37.149 --> 01:08:40.270
So I want to dispel one
misconception was that last

01:08:40.270 --> 01:08:44.500
time, I wasn't saying that you
can substitute style for

01:08:44.500 --> 01:08:46.859
preparation and really
knowing the material.

01:08:46.859 --> 01:08:50.640
It's really that I wanted to up
the importance that people

01:08:50.640 --> 01:08:55.490
give to what people would call
style by saying that the way

01:08:55.490 --> 01:08:57.950
you present, how you
present, is as

01:08:57.950 --> 01:08:59.380
important as what you present.

01:08:59.380 --> 01:09:02.359
In fact, it is, to some extent,
what you present.

01:09:02.359 --> 01:09:04.870
If, for example, you're very
interested in the material,

01:09:04.870 --> 01:09:08.810
and you present it in that way,
well, the students are

01:09:08.810 --> 01:09:12.630
very naturally going to become
interested in the material.

01:09:12.630 --> 01:09:14.609
As a test of this, you can
actually do little home

01:09:14.609 --> 01:09:16.870
experiments on this principle.

01:09:16.870 --> 01:09:18.014
So just go around to somebody.

01:09:18.014 --> 01:09:20.630
You can do these little like
Candid Camera experiments.

01:09:20.630 --> 01:09:24.899
Just go up to them and smile,
just like this, and then watch

01:09:24.899 --> 01:09:25.930
what they do.

01:09:25.930 --> 01:09:27.830
And a whole bunch of people
actually just smiled back at

01:09:27.830 --> 01:09:30.560
me for no reason at all,
just because I smiled.

01:09:30.560 --> 01:09:31.939
Now, not no reason at all.

01:09:31.939 --> 01:09:33.750
It's because we're
social creatures.

01:09:33.750 --> 01:09:37.399
We're programmed from millions
of years of evolution to pick

01:09:37.399 --> 01:09:40.689
up other people's emotions
and ways of being.

01:09:40.689 --> 01:09:43.229
So if you're enthusiastic about
the material, if you're

01:09:43.229 --> 01:09:44.840
interested in it, and you
present it like it's

01:09:44.840 --> 01:09:47.910
important, well, that actually
gets transmitted very

01:09:47.910 --> 01:09:51.010
effectively and picked up
at the other end very

01:09:51.010 --> 01:09:51.720
effectively.

01:09:51.720 --> 01:09:53.720
So actually, that is part
of the content.

01:09:53.720 --> 01:09:56.910
So I wouldn't say style is
separate from the content.

01:09:56.910 --> 01:10:00.060
How you present, how you think
about the material is a

01:10:00.060 --> 01:10:02.350
crucially important part
of the material.

01:10:02.350 --> 01:10:04.650
Because that's when students are
going to be taking away.

01:10:04.650 --> 01:10:06.700
And that's going to be affecting
how they think about

01:10:06.700 --> 01:10:07.650
the material.

01:10:07.650 --> 01:10:12.190
So it's not just focusing
on style--

01:10:12.190 --> 01:10:14.250
that sort of gives it too
little importance.

01:10:14.250 --> 01:10:16.430
Instead, yeah, how do you think
about all those issues

01:10:16.430 --> 01:10:19.010
as well as surviving your
research grant?

01:10:19.010 --> 01:10:22.450
And again, there I would
say the way to do

01:10:22.450 --> 01:10:24.710
it is to start slow.

01:10:24.710 --> 01:10:27.970
When you're an assistant
professor, you need to focus

01:10:27.970 --> 01:10:29.430
on your research
to get tenure.

01:10:29.430 --> 01:10:32.250
So focus on your research and
just try small teaching

01:10:32.250 --> 01:10:34.480
experiments bit by bit.

01:10:34.480 --> 01:10:38.170
Maybe in your first year, just
try putting in one small

01:10:38.170 --> 01:10:42.170
conceptual question per
lecture or per week.

01:10:42.170 --> 01:10:44.400
And if that goes OK, maybe
try longer ones.

01:10:44.400 --> 01:10:47.340
Try more the next semester
or the next year.

01:10:47.340 --> 01:10:49.070
So just try small things.

01:10:49.070 --> 01:10:51.620
And as they work, grow them.

01:10:51.620 --> 01:10:54.510
So that's one way, so you don't
have to sacrifice your

01:10:54.510 --> 01:10:57.570
research and hose yourself.

01:10:57.570 --> 01:11:01.600
So preparation time, as well--
so try to borrow notes from

01:11:01.600 --> 01:11:02.460
colleagues.

01:11:02.460 --> 01:11:06.640
Try to get as much from other
people as you can share.

01:11:06.640 --> 01:11:08.295
Talent invents, genius steals.

01:11:08.295 --> 01:11:11.570
So steal all the good
stuff around you.

01:11:11.570 --> 01:11:14.380
So another one is how does this
work in the real world,

01:11:14.380 --> 01:11:15.910
which is basically
the same thing.

01:11:15.910 --> 01:11:17.800
So what I'm trying to do in this
class is show you general

01:11:17.800 --> 01:11:22.640
principles that you can use
always to guide yourself in as

01:11:22.640 --> 01:11:25.340
far as you want to go
in your teaching.

01:11:25.340 --> 01:11:28.400
So now how far you go in your
particular situation depends

01:11:28.400 --> 01:11:32.700
on your situation and how much
importance you put on doing

01:11:32.700 --> 01:11:36.570
new teaching methods, new
experiments right then.

01:11:36.570 --> 01:11:39.490
But I'm not saying you have to
start everything tomorrow,

01:11:39.490 --> 01:11:42.090
like the first day you're a TA,
all of sudden throw out

01:11:42.090 --> 01:11:45.000
all the regular stuff and
do everything like I'm

01:11:45.000 --> 01:11:45.770
demonstrating now.

01:11:45.770 --> 01:11:48.840
I'm showing you this as
examples to illustrate

01:11:48.840 --> 01:11:52.130
principles for directions you
could go and for threads you

01:11:52.130 --> 01:11:55.670
can pick up as you see best.

01:11:55.670 --> 01:11:58.080
Syllabus and logistics
for this class--

01:11:58.080 --> 01:11:59.550
any exams or problem sets?

01:11:59.550 --> 01:12:02.810
Yeah, there's problem sets,
which you've seen one already.

01:12:02.810 --> 01:12:05.520
No exams.

01:12:05.520 --> 01:12:07.610
And so how are you
being evaluated?

01:12:07.610 --> 01:12:10.060
Basically again, very
light touch.

01:12:10.060 --> 01:12:11.510
Basically, just make a
reasonable effort on the

01:12:11.510 --> 01:12:14.050
problem sets, and
you'll be fine.

01:12:14.050 --> 01:12:17.150
I'm hoping basically that the
material's interesting enough

01:12:17.150 --> 01:12:21.010
that you don't need a stick
beating you, saying, oh, you

01:12:21.010 --> 01:12:23.310
must do this, you must do
that, you must do this.

01:12:23.310 --> 01:12:24.630
It's not a required course.

01:12:24.630 --> 01:12:26.710
People are taking it really
because they're interested.

01:12:26.710 --> 01:12:29.700
So I'm not going to try to ruin
that with a whole bunch

01:12:29.700 --> 01:12:33.410
of grading sticks.

01:12:33.410 --> 01:12:36.150
Does it matter which subject
number we're assigned for?

01:12:36.150 --> 01:12:38.610
No, and I don't even remember
what the subject numbers are.

01:12:38.610 --> 01:12:40.600
I know 595, and there's
a whole bunch of them.

01:12:40.600 --> 01:12:41.620
So I just write et cetera.

01:12:41.620 --> 01:12:44.740
No, it doesn't matter,
as far as I know.

01:12:44.740 --> 01:12:46.270
Could we have a break
after one hour?

01:12:46.270 --> 01:12:47.330
Yeah, I think that's
a good idea.

01:12:47.330 --> 01:12:50.230
So I'll give everyone like a
two- or three-minute break at

01:12:50.230 --> 01:12:52.300
the hour just so you can
stand and get your

01:12:52.300 --> 01:12:54.100
blood flowing again.

01:12:54.100 --> 01:12:56.370
Biology examples-- can we
have biology examples?

01:12:56.370 --> 01:12:57.290
A fair point--

01:12:57.290 --> 01:13:00.550
so actually, today our first
example of equations is a

01:13:00.550 --> 01:13:02.630
biology example, amazingly.

01:13:06.060 --> 01:13:08.430
OK, so now, interactive
teaching-- how do you teach a

01:13:08.430 --> 01:13:10.450
class interactively if
you have a lot of

01:13:10.450 --> 01:13:12.020
material to get through?

01:13:12.020 --> 01:13:13.200
This is a very interesting
question.

01:13:13.200 --> 01:13:14.850
It comes up quite often.

01:13:14.850 --> 01:13:17.850
And the answer is that
you don't get

01:13:17.850 --> 01:13:20.280
through it in the lecture.

01:13:20.280 --> 01:13:23.010
So the lecture is a terrible
place to get

01:13:23.010 --> 01:13:25.090
through lots of material.

01:13:25.090 --> 01:13:28.050
In fact, even the word "get
through," "cover"--

01:13:28.050 --> 01:13:30.860
those all have the wrong
sense to them.

01:13:30.860 --> 01:13:34.660
And so Victor Weisskopf, MIT
physics professor for many

01:13:34.660 --> 01:13:38.750
years, he said-- and I think
it's a great saying--

01:13:38.750 --> 01:13:42.140
instead of covering a lot of
material, I prefer to uncover

01:13:42.140 --> 01:13:44.630
a few key ideas.

01:13:44.630 --> 01:13:48.350
So uncover is the right verb.

01:13:48.350 --> 01:13:51.830
Cover has the sense
of smother.

01:13:51.830 --> 01:13:53.220
You can't see it anymore.

01:13:53.220 --> 01:13:56.260
And that is what happens when
you cover too much material.

01:13:56.260 --> 01:14:00.385
You want to uncover a few ideas
and let them bloom.

01:14:00.385 --> 01:14:03.720
So a lecture is something that's
paced at human scale.

01:14:03.720 --> 01:14:07.180
You talk at maybe 150
words a minute.

01:14:07.180 --> 01:14:09.040
People can't write that fast.

01:14:09.040 --> 01:14:11.930
They can write maybe
15 words a minute.

01:14:11.930 --> 01:14:14.300
Reading is much faster.

01:14:14.300 --> 01:14:18.220
Reading-- people can read 300,
maybe 400 words a minute.

01:14:18.220 --> 01:14:21.070
So if you have lots of material
to get through, don't

01:14:21.070 --> 01:14:24.410
fall into the trap of putting it
all on the blackboard or on

01:14:24.410 --> 01:14:25.840
the overhead slides.

01:14:25.840 --> 01:14:29.110
And we'll talk about that in
the session on making good

01:14:29.110 --> 01:14:31.020
slides and using
the blackboard.

01:14:31.020 --> 01:14:33.800
You want key ideas
to be there.

01:14:33.800 --> 01:14:38.030
And you can leave lots of
the details for reading.

01:14:38.030 --> 01:14:40.310
So that's one answer.

01:14:40.310 --> 01:14:42.510
The other answer is that
sometimes, actually, I think

01:14:42.510 --> 01:14:44.500
one of the fundamental problems
with so much teaching

01:14:44.500 --> 01:14:46.600
is that we try to cover
too much material.

01:14:46.600 --> 01:14:50.140
And one of the goals should be
for good teaching is to reduce

01:14:50.140 --> 01:14:51.950
how much material one covers.

01:14:51.950 --> 01:14:56.520
And there's a simple estimation
argument to show

01:14:56.520 --> 01:14:57.775
why that's important.

01:14:57.775 --> 01:15:01.470
The estimation argument is that
basically, suppose you

01:15:01.470 --> 01:15:03.660
cover 100% of the material.

01:15:03.660 --> 01:15:06.180
But because it's so much
material, students remember

01:15:06.180 --> 01:15:09.130
only 10%, and really learn only
10%, which I think is

01:15:09.130 --> 01:15:11.280
actually a reasonable
estimate.

01:15:11.280 --> 01:15:12.700
Because they're just
so overloaded.

01:15:12.700 --> 01:15:14.930
They have no time to make
connections, and it just

01:15:14.930 --> 01:15:15.670
flitters away.

01:15:15.670 --> 01:15:17.850
So 10% is all they retain.

01:15:17.850 --> 01:15:21.310
Well, you could cover, say,
half the material.

01:15:21.310 --> 01:15:24.060
And let's say that they still
don't remember everything,

01:15:24.060 --> 01:15:24.860
even though you've done half.

01:15:24.860 --> 01:15:27.140
Maybe they remember half of
that, because they have time

01:15:27.140 --> 01:15:29.490
to struggle with it,
make connections.

01:15:29.490 --> 01:15:32.850
So now, they're at half of half,
which is 25% retention

01:15:32.850 --> 01:15:34.130
instead of 10%.

01:15:34.130 --> 01:15:36.390
So that's a plausible model.

01:15:36.390 --> 01:15:38.830
I'm not claiming those figures
are actually based on exact

01:15:38.830 --> 01:15:39.710
research or anything.

01:15:39.710 --> 01:15:42.380
But just a plausible model for
how reducing the amount of

01:15:42.380 --> 01:15:45.310
stuff you cover can actually
increase learning.

01:15:45.310 --> 01:15:48.380
So try to reduce material
when possible.

01:15:48.380 --> 01:15:50.210
Almost always, there's
too much material.

01:15:53.270 --> 01:15:55.470
OK, so again, how do
you pace lectures?

01:15:55.470 --> 01:15:57.820
If you do too many demos and
you have less material,

01:15:57.820 --> 01:15:59.820
advanced students
might get bored.

01:15:59.820 --> 01:16:02.750
Actually, I find advanced
students are actually quite

01:16:02.750 --> 01:16:05.680
interested in demos and
questions like this that we

01:16:05.680 --> 01:16:06.770
used last time.

01:16:06.770 --> 01:16:09.220
They want to really understand
what's going on.

01:16:09.220 --> 01:16:11.790
And it's those kind of questions
that help them.

01:16:11.790 --> 01:16:13.220
Covering lots of material--

01:16:13.220 --> 01:16:15.700
again, they can read it in a
book much faster than you can

01:16:15.700 --> 01:16:16.690
write it on the board.

01:16:16.690 --> 01:16:19.240
So put it there.

01:16:19.240 --> 01:16:21.000
Can these principles be
applied to upper-level

01:16:21.000 --> 01:16:22.130
graduate classes?

01:16:22.130 --> 01:16:23.460
For sure.

01:16:23.460 --> 01:16:25.520
You can apply them all the way
from kindergarten through

01:16:25.520 --> 01:16:27.280
graduate school because they're
really based on how

01:16:27.280 --> 01:16:28.540
people think.

01:16:28.540 --> 01:16:32.100
And they're based on common ways
that people perceive the

01:16:32.100 --> 01:16:32.980
world and reason.

01:16:32.980 --> 01:16:34.380
And that doesn't change--

01:16:34.380 --> 01:16:36.840
I mean, life does change when
you become a graduate student.

01:16:36.840 --> 01:16:38.650
But your whole way of
looking at the world

01:16:38.650 --> 01:16:39.900
doesn't change that much.

01:16:43.170 --> 01:16:45.170
So how do you deal with
classes where someone

01:16:45.170 --> 01:16:47.440
dominates a discussion or the
class does not like to

01:16:47.440 --> 01:16:47.820
participate?

01:16:47.820 --> 01:16:50.270
Sort of two ends of
the same coin.

01:16:50.270 --> 01:16:53.080
So what I like to do is if
someone keeps trying to say

01:16:53.080 --> 01:16:56.320
stuff, I just say, oh, well,
actually I want everybody to

01:16:56.320 --> 01:16:58.040
participate.

01:16:58.040 --> 01:16:59.690
Could I hear from someone
I haven't heard from?

01:16:59.690 --> 01:17:00.680
Just with a light touch.

01:17:00.680 --> 01:17:03.070
You don't have to make
a big confrontation

01:17:03.070 --> 01:17:04.325
in class about it.

01:17:04.325 --> 01:17:06.570
If people don't like
to participate--

01:17:06.570 --> 01:17:08.850
for example, suppose you ask
them to discuss with each

01:17:08.850 --> 01:17:09.990
other and they don't.

01:17:09.990 --> 01:17:12.430
So here's a trick I learned
actually from one of the

01:17:12.430 --> 01:17:16.080
teaching seminars when I was in
England, which is that you

01:17:16.080 --> 01:17:19.600
just turn your back.

01:17:19.600 --> 01:17:20.990
And why do you do that?

01:17:20.990 --> 01:17:25.450
Well, your back is not as
interesting as your front.

01:17:25.450 --> 01:17:28.830
So students are actually taught
with, say, 12 years of

01:17:28.830 --> 01:17:31.440
teaching to watch the teacher,
watch the teacher.

01:17:31.440 --> 01:17:33.420
So one of the reluctances to
talk to each other is they're

01:17:33.420 --> 01:17:34.750
watching the teacher, figuring
out what the

01:17:34.750 --> 01:17:36.680
teacher's saying and doing.

01:17:36.680 --> 01:17:41.210
Kind of like Clever Hans was
watching his trainer--

01:17:41.210 --> 01:17:43.502
do I do more clips on my foot?

01:17:43.502 --> 01:17:44.490
Is that 42?

01:17:44.490 --> 01:17:46.230
6 times 7--

01:17:46.230 --> 01:17:47.020
OK.

01:17:47.020 --> 01:17:49.930
So students are actually taught,
basically, after 12

01:17:49.930 --> 01:17:53.180
years of conditioning, do
that very automatically.

01:17:53.180 --> 01:17:54.850
So you just have to break
that conditioning a bit.

01:17:54.850 --> 01:17:57.150
If you just turn around, there's
nothing really that

01:17:57.150 --> 01:17:58.800
interesting to look at,
unless you're maybe--

01:17:58.800 --> 01:18:03.040
I don't know, some fashion model
or a GQ model, which I'm

01:18:03.040 --> 01:18:04.720
not claiming to be.

01:18:04.720 --> 01:18:07.680
So then the students will just
naturally be more likely to

01:18:07.680 --> 01:18:08.340
talk to each other.

01:18:08.340 --> 01:18:09.950
So you create the conditions
for that.

01:18:09.950 --> 01:18:10.820
Another one--

01:18:10.820 --> 01:18:12.270
and I often use this
trick, because it's

01:18:12.270 --> 01:18:13.340
actually not a trick--

01:18:13.340 --> 01:18:14.530
is sometimes I'm thirsty.

01:18:14.530 --> 01:18:17.420
I just walk out of the room and
go get a drink of water.

01:18:17.420 --> 01:18:19.440
So if it's an interesting enough
question, the students

01:18:19.440 --> 01:18:20.870
will be talking to each
other about it.

01:18:20.870 --> 01:18:24.240
And there's definitely not you
around there, watching them or

01:18:24.240 --> 01:18:25.990
worrying them, for
them to focus on.

01:18:25.990 --> 01:18:28.270
So that's one very
useful trick.

01:18:28.270 --> 01:18:31.810
Generally, though, the overall
point is if the class doesn't

01:18:31.810 --> 01:18:35.080
want to participate, you just
make it more and more safe to

01:18:35.080 --> 01:18:35.455
participate.

01:18:35.455 --> 01:18:37.820
You make sure you never
criticize people if they say

01:18:37.820 --> 01:18:39.340
something that wasn't right.

01:18:39.340 --> 01:18:42.030
You make sure you value
the wrong answers

01:18:42.030 --> 01:18:43.060
and you explain why.

01:18:43.060 --> 01:18:46.450
So all of the things I talked
about last time about safety

01:18:46.450 --> 01:18:48.630
means you just have to do them
double if people aren't

01:18:48.630 --> 01:18:49.880
participating.

01:18:56.370 --> 01:18:58.320
How do you cope with a
variety of confidence

01:18:58.320 --> 01:19:00.740
levels among students?

01:19:00.740 --> 01:19:01.570
Also interesting.

01:19:01.570 --> 01:19:05.210
So there, I find actually
that most

01:19:05.210 --> 01:19:07.770
students aren't very confident.

01:19:07.770 --> 01:19:09.020
They have different levels--

01:19:11.450 --> 01:19:14.060
they're all generally much
lower than you think.

01:19:14.060 --> 01:19:16.960
So they do have some different
levels, but it's generally

01:19:16.960 --> 01:19:18.520
overall lower than you think.

01:19:18.520 --> 01:19:20.680
So I spend more of my effort
making sure everyone feels

01:19:20.680 --> 01:19:22.000
comfortable.

01:19:22.000 --> 01:19:25.750
But again, if some students are
much more confident than

01:19:25.750 --> 01:19:29.360
others, I try to mix up the
level of questions that I ask.

01:19:29.360 --> 01:19:31.530
I ask some questions that I know
most people are not going

01:19:31.530 --> 01:19:33.690
to be able to answer and some
questions that I know most

01:19:33.690 --> 01:19:37.290
people will answer, just so
everyone has something.

01:19:37.290 --> 01:19:39.910
And then on the problem
sets as well--

01:19:39.910 --> 01:19:41.080
warm-up problems, regular

01:19:41.080 --> 01:19:43.720
problems, really hard problems.

01:19:43.720 --> 01:19:47.700
Like in Donald Knuth's
textbooks, the fifth set of,

01:19:47.700 --> 01:19:50.130
kind of, problem at the end of
the chapters is unsolved

01:19:50.130 --> 01:19:51.520
research problems.

01:19:51.520 --> 01:19:52.250
And you never know.

01:19:52.250 --> 01:19:54.210
Someone might actually
solve one of them.

01:19:54.210 --> 01:19:56.680
So you can put something
for everyone in there.

01:19:59.690 --> 01:20:00.820
What about the left brain?

01:20:00.820 --> 01:20:04.076
Surely humor and demos can't
take you all the way.

01:20:04.076 --> 01:20:05.770
Yeah, and that's true.

01:20:05.770 --> 01:20:09.200
And so my answer to what about
the left brain is that the

01:20:09.200 --> 01:20:13.460
left brain is what basically
most teaching has focused on

01:20:13.460 --> 01:20:16.370
for most people's experience
over the last 15 or 16 years.

01:20:16.370 --> 01:20:19.020
So I'm not saying, forget
about the left brain.

01:20:19.020 --> 01:20:21.430
I'm saying that you basically
already know how to do the

01:20:21.430 --> 01:20:23.480
left-brain side of teaching.

01:20:23.480 --> 01:20:25.520
You have so many
models of that.

01:20:25.520 --> 01:20:27.670
It is pretty much what we
think of as teaching.

01:20:27.670 --> 01:20:30.030
You go up to the blackboard, and
you write down a series of

01:20:30.030 --> 01:20:31.720
symbols one after
another, write

01:20:31.720 --> 01:20:32.940
down a series of equations.

01:20:32.940 --> 01:20:35.990
So you already have
models for that.

01:20:35.990 --> 01:20:37.910
And we'll talk about how
to improve those.

01:20:37.910 --> 01:20:39.800
But I'm not so worried
about that part.

01:20:39.800 --> 01:20:41.970
What I'm worried about is
the neglected part.

01:20:41.970 --> 01:20:44.500
So this you could think
of as the balance.

01:20:44.500 --> 01:20:46.840
And then you'll be able to find
ways of integrating the

01:20:46.840 --> 01:20:47.370
left brain.

01:20:47.370 --> 01:20:50.300
And we'll do left-brain
things, equations.

01:20:50.300 --> 01:20:52.870
But how do you integrate that
with all the quote "right

01:20:52.870 --> 01:20:54.300
brain," the humor
and the demos?

01:20:58.690 --> 01:21:00.450
How do you project confidence?

01:21:00.450 --> 01:21:02.710
Fake it till you make it?

01:21:02.710 --> 01:21:06.130
Yeah, that's basically right.

01:21:06.130 --> 01:21:10.500
So one way is to actually make
sure your voice is clear.

01:21:10.500 --> 01:21:15.950
So to do that, my piano teacher
in graduate school--

01:21:15.950 --> 01:21:18.080
actually, she was a voice
teacher, as well.

01:21:18.080 --> 01:21:22.456
She gave me a really useful
exercise, which is--

01:21:22.456 --> 01:21:25.320
I do this for like 30 seconds
before I come to lecture.

01:21:25.320 --> 01:21:29.510
So the exercise is you first
just close your lips.

01:21:29.510 --> 01:21:32.780
And you mmm, you hum.

01:21:32.780 --> 01:21:34.150
So we'll all do this together.

01:21:34.150 --> 01:21:37.210
So you hum until you can feel
it vibrating in your nose.

01:21:37.210 --> 01:21:37.800
That's step one.

01:21:37.800 --> 01:21:38.740
So let's all do that together.

01:21:38.740 --> 01:21:43.670
[HUMMING]

01:21:43.670 --> 01:21:46.000
And if you have hay fever, you
can tell if you're doing it

01:21:46.000 --> 01:21:47.300
right in the spring.

01:21:47.300 --> 01:21:49.290
Because you'll dislodge
pollen grains and

01:21:49.290 --> 01:21:50.260
you'll probably sneeze.

01:21:50.260 --> 01:21:51.840
That's what I find
in the spring.

01:21:51.840 --> 01:21:54.010
When I do that, I actually
start sneezing.

01:21:54.010 --> 01:21:56.800
My theory is that I'm dislodging
pollen grains and

01:21:56.800 --> 01:21:59.110
then I'm sneezing as
a result of them.

01:21:59.110 --> 01:22:00.170
So mmm--

01:22:00.170 --> 01:22:02.610
so now you've got a
resonance up here.

01:22:02.610 --> 01:22:07.610
And now what you want to do is
with the same mmm sound, now

01:22:07.610 --> 01:22:10.350
do it in the back of your teeth
with your mouth closed.

01:22:10.350 --> 01:22:11.890
So you feel behind your teeth.

01:22:11.890 --> 01:22:14.600
So we'll do step one
and then step two.

01:22:14.600 --> 01:22:16.280
Mmm and then the teeth.

01:22:16.280 --> 01:22:18.010
Mmm, teeth.

01:22:18.010 --> 01:22:20.250
[HUMMING]

01:22:20.250 --> 01:22:22.580
And you should feel
in your lips

01:22:22.580 --> 01:22:24.090
vibrating, kind of tickling.

01:22:24.090 --> 01:22:26.520
OK, so that's step two.

01:22:26.520 --> 01:22:31.100
Step three is to then make the
vowel sound that is most

01:22:31.100 --> 01:22:33.140
likely to make your mouth
resonate and be

01:22:33.140 --> 01:22:34.020
really wide and open.

01:22:34.020 --> 01:22:41.280
That's E. So we'll go hmm
and them mmm and eee.

01:22:41.280 --> 01:22:42.940
OK, so nose--

01:22:42.940 --> 01:22:44.950
[HUMMING]

01:22:44.950 --> 01:22:45.320
lips--

01:22:45.320 --> 01:22:46.790
[HUMMING]

01:22:46.790 --> 01:22:48.040
eeeeeee.

01:22:50.550 --> 01:22:51.330
OK, that's step three.

01:22:51.330 --> 01:22:53.580
And then the final step is
you just add some words.

01:22:53.580 --> 01:22:55.050
You modulate it with words.

01:22:55.050 --> 01:22:57.640
All right, so I'll give
you a demonstration.

01:22:57.640 --> 01:22:59.252
Then we'll do all
of it together.

01:22:59.252 --> 01:23:00.520
[HUMMING]

01:23:00.520 --> 01:23:04.280
Eeeee-- (SPEAKING ON SAME
NOTE) how are youuuuuu.

01:23:04.280 --> 01:23:06.300
OK, so now, that sounds
a bit strange.

01:23:06.300 --> 01:23:09.230
But you find after you
do that, your voice

01:23:09.230 --> 01:23:10.330
is much more resonant.

01:23:10.330 --> 01:23:12.420
Actually, I can hear
it right now.

01:23:12.420 --> 01:23:14.270
To my own ears, my voice
sounds much more

01:23:14.270 --> 01:23:16.200
resonant and clear.

01:23:16.200 --> 01:23:17.606
So let's do that.

01:23:17.606 --> 01:23:21.890
[HUMMING]

01:23:21.890 --> 01:23:24.170
Eeeee--

01:23:24.170 --> 01:23:28.030
(SPEAKING ON SAME NOTE)
how are youuuuuu.

01:23:28.030 --> 01:23:30.510
So you'll find, actually, what
you've done is you've shifted

01:23:30.510 --> 01:23:34.800
your voice from here, where it
just makes your throat tight,

01:23:34.800 --> 01:23:36.070
to the front.

01:23:36.070 --> 01:23:39.140
And just by doing that,
you will project.

01:23:39.140 --> 01:23:42.210
And by projecting, you actually
sound more confident.

01:23:42.210 --> 01:23:43.460
And you'll feel more
confident.

01:23:45.860 --> 01:23:47.590
So that's one way.

01:23:47.590 --> 01:23:50.460
But another way is to be
confident of your material.

01:23:50.460 --> 01:23:53.190
And another way is, as you said
in the question, just

01:23:53.190 --> 01:23:54.516
fake it till you make it.

01:23:58.070 --> 01:23:59.660
Now, there's a few
more questions.

01:23:59.660 --> 01:24:02.820
I'll answer some of them
on the website.

01:24:02.820 --> 01:24:05.410
But I wanted to answer
one more.

01:24:05.410 --> 01:24:08.640
How long did it take you to
become such a good teacher?

01:24:08.640 --> 01:24:11.650
So I'm glad people think I'm a
good teacher, or at least one

01:24:11.650 --> 01:24:14.250
person thinks so.

01:24:14.250 --> 01:24:16.340
But there's a general answer
to that question, which is

01:24:16.340 --> 01:24:18.360
actually going to be one of the
topics today, which is,

01:24:18.360 --> 01:24:21.660
how do you become an
expert in anything?

01:24:21.660 --> 01:24:26.370
And the first example I'm
going to show you-- it's

01:24:26.370 --> 01:24:27.740
biology equations.

01:24:27.740 --> 01:24:28.740
I'm going to use that.

01:24:28.740 --> 01:24:32.340
And then after that, when I
talk about expertise in

01:24:32.340 --> 01:24:36.850
general, not just in teaching,
and where that comes from.

01:24:36.850 --> 01:24:40.530
And I'll show you the results
of some studies.

01:24:40.530 --> 01:24:42.440
And then I'll come back
to that question.

01:24:42.440 --> 01:24:45.980
And I'll hopefully
answer it then.

01:24:45.980 --> 01:24:48.930
So those are I would say
2/3 of the questions.

01:24:48.930 --> 01:24:52.770
The ones I haven't answered
I'll try to answer online.

01:24:52.770 --> 01:24:55.730
And I'll pass out these
in just a moment.

01:24:55.730 --> 01:24:58.550
But right now, what we're going
to do is we're going to

01:24:58.550 --> 01:25:01.000
do the first example
of equations,

01:25:01.000 --> 01:25:02.360
which is from biology.

01:25:02.360 --> 01:25:04.400
Now, before I do that, any
questions that have occurred

01:25:04.400 --> 01:25:07.585
to you meanwhile?

